1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:20,000
This is Emilye Crosby on December 8th, 2015, and we're in Baltimore at Betty Garman Robinson's home.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:27,000
We're interviewing Dorothy Zellner, Dottie Zellner, as part of the Civil Rights History Project,

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:34,000
sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

5
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:41,000
Also with us is John Bishop and Guha Shankar is here as well.

6
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Dottie, could you start by telling us when and where you were born and about your family?

7
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Yes, I was born in New York City, January 14th, 1938.

8
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:59,000
The oldest of three children. My parents are both immigrants.

9
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:06,000
My father's people came from Lithuania to England. He was born in England.

10
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:13,000
He emigrated at age 11 in 1910 to Toronto Canada.

11
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:22,000
My mother was born in Kiev, which is now the Ukraine, but she always considered it to be Russia.

12
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:30,000
A baby norm is at six months to Toronto Canada. Both of them emigrated to the United States.

13
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:36,000
They were married here and they were both naturalized. I'm the oldest of three children.

14
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:43,000
My sister is Eleanor. I yearned a half younger than I and my brother Jonathan. It's five years younger.

15
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:47,000
Can you describe your growing up years?

16
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:56,000
My father was a dentist and he became a dentist because as a Jewish person in Canada he couldn't be a teacher.

17
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:03,000
There was one teacher in the entire country in Canada in the 30s, one Jewish teacher.

18
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:13,000
So he became a dentist second best and he migrated to the United States in 1929, a very key year.

19
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:22,000
Didn't get it to have a job for three years and actually was hospitalized at one point for malnutrition.

20
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:29,000
I'd say the big factor of my growing up as a young child was World War II.

21
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:39,000
I have very distinct memories of air raid drills and pulling down black curtains on the windows.

22
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:45,000
My father was eccentric, to say the least.

23
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:55,000
He and my mother, who was his quote-unquote nurse, his assistant, they worked in the front of our apartment and we lived in the back three rooms.

24
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:10,000
It was a typical immigrant mom and pop operation, differing only in vocation from many other hundreds of thousands of families who also lived and worked in the same place.

25
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:15,000
My father was totally worked up about the war.

26
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:21,000
In between patients he would run back into our living space which was three rooms in the back.

27
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:26,000
He would turn on the radio to get the war news.

28
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,000
My father was left wing, my mother was left wing.

29
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:36,000
They were both highly involved in the issues of the day.

30
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Both of them had come from Orthodox Jewish families.

31
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:46,000
They were not Orthodox, they were secular but quite Jewish.

32
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:51,000
I remember the war was living in our house.

33
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:56,000
The war was another member of the family.

34
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:03,000
Another early memory I had was that my father was a great movie fan.

35
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:07,000
He took us to the movies.

36
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Who us was? I must have been about seven or eight.

37
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
I think the war was still going on.

38
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
There was a newsreel that accompanied the film.

39
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000
It must have been a cartoon movie that he took us to.

40
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:26,000
There was a newsreel film of the war which he was not anticipating.

41
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:34,000
I remember seeing a child hobbling along with crutches and one missing leg.

42
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:44,000
I became so frightened and upset that I crawled under the seat in the movie theater and they had to pull me out.

43
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:53,000
The war was this ever-present specter in our house.

44
00:04:53,000 --> 00:05:01,000
After the war I came across a book called The Black Book which was in my parents' library.

45
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:08,000
It was a picture book of the concentration camps.

46
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:16,000
I remember reading it and I guess I was about eight then.

47
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:21,000
Being the oldest child I was very protective of my younger sips.

48
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:24,000
I took the book and I threw it in the garbage.

49
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:29,000
The garbage cans were in the hall outside our apartment.

50
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:35,000
When my mother saw the book in the garbage she had a fit.

51
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
My father had a fit too.

52
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:47,000
Their attitude was not that I as a young child had been petrified by these photos but that I had had the temerity to throw away a book.

53
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:51,000
You never throw away a book.

54
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:56,000
That was the message that was sent to me.

55
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:09,000
The question about the war was now looking back on it a lot of fear and were we as Jews going to survive?

56
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:15,000
If you had asked me that at age 7 I would not have been able to articulate that at all.

57
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:19,000
That was what was simmering around us.

58
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:28,000
When I give talks now which I have been doing for 30 years I tell people that it was not just a theoretical question.

59
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:35,000
Were we going to make it was a real question?

60
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:40,000
If things had happened differently we wouldn't have made it.

61
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:45,000
When my father was cheering on the Red Army he was very correct to do that.

62
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:54,000
When the German army would possibly have triumph.

63
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:59,000
It was a very vivid thing. Hitler was a real person.

64
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:03,000
These were all real people.

65
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:07,000
You mentioned that your father couldn't be a teacher at Toronto.

66
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:11,000
So they can't have that kind of a television or a teacher at Toronto?

67
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:18,000
It was a statutory or whether it was custom but it was a very anti-Semitic country.

68
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:26,000
He always felt that it was very provincial, very boring, very wasp, very provincial.

69
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,000
Yes.

70
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
Yes.

71
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:36,000
It was because both of them were exposed to the broader world.

72
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:44,000
They were both on the left and Toronto was like being in Ischgibbibble Idaho.

73
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,000
Something like that.

74
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,000
That's why they came.

75
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:53,000
You mentioned you talked about the war a lot and found a second other part of your house.

76
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
It was a real person.

77
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:07,000
I don't remember their actual words but they talked about it.

78
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:12,000
They talked about what was happening to the extent that they knew.

79
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:20,000
And by extension their concern about Jews was extended outward to other people.

80
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:25,000
Other people who were marginalized and in difficulty.

81
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:30,000
And I remember asking him when I was about eight or nine I said,

82
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:33,000
Daddy, I don't understand.

83
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:38,000
I said, how did they know who we were?

84
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:41,000
So I must have been quite preoccupied with it.

85
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:45,000
And he said that a lot of that they didn't know.

86
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:49,000
And that's as it turns out, that's why they had to register everybody.

87
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:52,000
Because they didn't know.

88
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:58,000
And I remember thinking, well, a lot of times they didn't know who we were.

89
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:02,000
But they would have known who a black person was.

90
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:11,000
So from our early age I think there was a sort of an awareness.

91
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:16,000
And I do remember when I was about five, my one of my younger moments actually.

92
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:20,000
I remember getting on a bus with my mother in the city.

93
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:22,000
And there were some black people on the bus.

94
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:26,000
And I remember saying to her in a very loud voice,

95
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:30,000
why aren't they speaking to each other?

96
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,000
Are they angry with each other?

97
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,000
And she said, what do you mean?

98
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:37,000
I said, well, they're all in the same family.

99
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
Why aren't they talking?

100
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:45,000
And of course she, you know, she became mortified that had asked such question out loud.

101
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
And so I made a big impression on me.

102
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:53,000
That's why I remember that I had made some horrible faux pas.

103
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:58,000
But I was obviously very, I was conscious.

104
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:01,000
And I don't remember that they had very many black friends,

105
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,000
but they did have a few.

106
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:05,000
And my father had a few black patients.

107
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:14,000
And my father also was very, very, very devoted to the veterans of the Spanish Civil War.

108
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:20,000
And he had not gone to the Spanish Civil War to volunteer.

109
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:24,000
I don't know exactly why.

110
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:29,000
Later on when World War II was started,

111
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
he then had two children and he was in his 40s.

112
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:35,000
And he tried to enlist, but they wouldn't take him.

113
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:37,000
That he was too old.

114
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:42,000
But about the Spanish Civil War, he always treated all of the vets

115
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:45,000
that were in his practice free.

116
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:48,000
For the rest of their lives, the rest of his life.

117
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:53,000
And he repeated that with some of the people from SNCC.

118
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:58,000
And he treated them, you know, and he was only one part of, really,

119
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:06,000
I think, considerable number of medical people who took care of civil rights vets.

120
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:09,000
And let me hop to one story about that.

121
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:12,000
When Bill Hansen was in jail,

122
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:15,000
don't know where I must have been Arkansas,

123
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:21,000
and he got his job alvening, and his jaw was broken.

124
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,000
In alvening, they wired up his jaw together,

125
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:30,000
and they told him that he could get it unwired in a month.

126
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:33,000
So he had to walk around with his jaw wired together for a month.

127
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:37,000
And he was able to drink through a straw.

128
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:43,000
And on the day when, you know, the wires could be taken off,

129
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:48,000
I guess I arranged that my father would take out the wires.

130
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:52,000
So he came to the office, and remember my father took all the wires out.

131
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:59,000
And then Bill was totally crestful to find out that this had fallen on a Friday.

132
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:03,000
And as a Catholic, he couldn't eat meat.

133
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:10,000
And he had been longing to have a huge steak like this pig.

134
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:16,000
And he said, oh no, it's Friday, I have fish.

135
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:19,000
Of course, thinking back, oh, can you imagine?

136
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:23,000
I mean, such a thing happening today that would never happen to it.

137
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:29,000
So, you know, I don't know how many other people he treated,

138
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:33,000
but I remember, you know, Bill was...

139
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:36,000
So then my father had a whole bunch of friends who came over.

140
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:39,000
My mother had friends. They were all lefties.

141
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
They were very concerned about everything, everything.

142
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:47,000
I remember in high school, I came home one day,

143
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:50,000
and one of my father's friends were in the house.

144
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:53,000
My father loved his friends.

145
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:57,000
And I said, well, today we were told...

146
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:02,000
This was in 1954 now when I was in high school.

147
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:13,000
I said, I said in class that the United States was starting to send aid to the French to fight in Vietnam.

148
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:16,000
And the teacher said it was absolutely false.

149
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:24,000
And my father's friend saw two days later, he came in, he said, take this to your teacher.

150
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:31,000
It was an article in the New York Times, and I did, and I raised my hand, and I said,

151
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:39,000
I want you to know I read him the article, and he was very embarrassed. I'm happy to say.

152
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:42,000
So I sort of felt like there were a lot of...

153
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:45,000
There was some adults sort of cheering us on,

154
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:50,000
because then when we were in high school, we were in the depths of the McCarthy days,

155
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:58,000
and there were a lot of people who were sort of, I don't know, keeping an eye on us that we would be okay out in McCarthy days.

156
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:07,000
Now during the war, there was a feeling actually of camaraderie, and that dissipated soon enough,

157
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:12,000
and I'd say by 1949, now there were problems.

158
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:21,000
Now in our apartment building, which consisted of six floors with the fire escape out front,

159
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:28,000
which I made a mistake of describing as a tenement, in an article I wrote later on,

160
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:32,000
and my mother took high exception to this.

161
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:36,000
We never lived in a tenement, but actually it was a tenement.

162
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:39,000
A tenement is not a majority word actually.

163
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:48,000
Living in our house was a leading member of the Communist Party and his family.

164
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:58,000
And we were quite friendly with them, and in New York, in the apartment building,

165
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:05,000
where I lived till I was 13, and we became very friendly with that family.

166
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:19,000
And the father, the male parent of this family, was arrested in 1951 under the SNCC Act.

167
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:25,000
The SNCC Act charge, people don't remember this at all when I tell these young people,

168
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:34,000
the SNCC Act made it a crime to advocate and conspire.

169
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:43,000
No, conspire and advocate the overthrow of the US government by force and violence.

170
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:47,000
So first you had to advocate, and then you had to conspire.

171
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:53,000
It was two steps removed, at least from actual violence.

172
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:02,000
And not one of these people was ever convicted of ever even having a pea shooter, much less a gun.

173
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:15,000
It was extreme macarthiasum, and it was singling out this party as the sorts of wool, devils and evils.

174
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:25,000
So of course, I imagine we had FBI watching, and when he was arrested, the father was arrested,

175
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:31,000
it was seven o'clock in the morning. They came tramping up the stairs in the six-story building.

176
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:35,000
Everybody, all of us, knew who were in the house that this had happened.

177
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:40,000
This was very traumatic.

178
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:47,000
So I always felt growing up that I was definitely marginalized, definitely.

179
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:58,000
I knew I was in a group of very unpopular people, and by then of course, the macarthiasum was extreme.

180
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:03,000
I mean it's even hard to describe this to younger people. Here's an example.

181
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:08,000
When I was in high school, I was a junior in high school, so I graduated in 1955.

182
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:18,000
In 1954, our class decided that as a graduation speaker, we wanted to invite J. Robert Oppenheimer,

183
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:22,000
who was one of the atomic scientists.

184
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:31,000
This was so outlandish and extreme, viewed by the principal of our high school, that he refused.

185
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:42,000
Now, Oppenheimer was one of the semi-semi-suspect scientists working on the Manhattan Project.

186
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:52,000
Certainly not a raving red by any means, but nevertheless somebody who had criticized the building of the atomic bomb,

187
00:17:52,000 --> 00:18:00,000
that was his great sin, and who was reluctantly participating in, you know, re-orming with atomic weapons.

188
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:05,000
This was such an extreme thing that they almost closed down the school.

189
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:11,000
I mean it was an unbelievable thing, hard to even identify with.

190
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:15,000
So I don't know how deep you want to go.

191
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:23,000
I mean the signal event of my teenage life was when the Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were executed.

192
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:33,000
And my friend Freddie, the son of the family I was just talking about, he and I, and his mother and my mother,

193
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:39,000
the four of us went to Washington. I was 15, he was 14.

194
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:46,000
And while we were in Washington, the Supreme Court issued a stay of execution.

195
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:51,000
And instead of everybody coming back, a lot of people stayed over in Washington.

196
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:57,000
And Freddie's mother said he could stay and my mother very reluctantly said I could stay.

197
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:02,000
So there we were in front of the White House all night,

198
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:05,000
picketing in front of the White House.

199
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:14,000
And one of my memories is that along with us was picketing this young woman in high heels and it was Mary Travers,

200
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:21,000
soon to be in Peter Paul and Mary, who was then a couple of years older than I was.

201
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:23,000
And she was there.

202
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:34,000
So you can see coming into the movement, I was not your typical average, you know, American teenager.

203
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:44,000
I also, I was quite romantic. I think, I mean, I was living on books and stories about the war.

204
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:55,000
And I actually probably was a teenage expert on what had happened to the Jews, and particularly the stories about the Warsaw ghetto,

205
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:05,000
which is where the Jews were captured and from which they were brought to the extermination camps.

206
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:12,000
And in May, in April 1943, they had a revolt.

207
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:17,000
Six weeks, they held off the German army, the six weeks.

208
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:34,000
And this was the only civilian armed uprising, including, I've just been to Paris a month ago, including the Great French Resistance,

209
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:38,000
which fought for six days in Paris.

210
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:45,000
This was six weeks, fighting by desperate people who knew they were going to be killed and who just decided,

211
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:50,000
if they were going to go, they were bringing, bring as many of them as they could.

212
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:55,000
This made an indelible impression on me to this very day.

213
00:20:55,000 --> 00:21:10,000
To this very day, I consider it not only an obligation, but an honor, that if you are up against the fascists,

214
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:18,000
and you have no other recourse that you have to, you must bring as many of them as you can.

215
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:25,000
So by the time the civil rights movement came along, was there really a question.

216
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:30,000
Now there might have been a question, I think, Freddie urged me to go, other people urged me to go.

217
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:33,000
I don't think I was just sitting there thinking about this myself.

218
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:44,000
But I do remember, and I've talked about it many times, but I remember where I was even sitting when I read the paper, and I read the story about the sit-ins.

219
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:47,000
I remember every single thing about that.

220
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:51,000
You've alluded to the fact that you have vivid memories of reading about the sit-in movement.

221
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:55,000
Do you have memories of other elements of the civil rights movement?

222
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:57,000
Oh yes.

223
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:08,000
Well, somewhere along the line in high school, I joined the NAACP, and it was just, you know, with the friends that I had, especially being on the left.

224
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:13,000
I mean, it was a given, you were going to support black people.

225
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:20,000
And actually, I have to say that I have a totally thrilling memory that I will share with you.

226
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:26,000
I don't know how old that was. I made it 14 or 13 or 14.

227
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:35,000
Freddie's father was friends with Paul Robeson, who of course was a great, tremendous hero of my youth.

228
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:43,000
And Paul Robeson must have been coming to visit him, and my father must have been coming out of the office or something.

229
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:48,000
It was the daytime, and it was second avenue and 18th Street.

230
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:56,000
Across the street comes Freddie's father, Jerry, who was about 5'7".

231
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:02,000
My father, who was 5'2". No, maybe he was 5'4".

232
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:06,000
And Paul Robeson, who was about 7'2".

233
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:13,000
And they're walking across second avenue. Paul Robeson, oh my god.

234
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:21,000
So anyway, I wouldn't say that I don't remember going to Harlem.

235
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:30,000
I remember having some black friends, not really close black friends, but it was an article of faith that this is something that you would be involved in.

236
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:33,000
So when the bus boy cuts, the bus boy cut I remember.

237
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:40,000
I remember actually the day of Brown v. Board of Education, and everyone really getting excited.

238
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:47,000
And I remember those banner headlines. So Brown v. Board of Education was 54, so I was 16.

239
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:50,000
So I was 16.

240
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:54,000
And I remember going on demonstrations.

241
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:57,000
I guess it was about the bus boy cut.

242
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:01,000
I mean, the bus boy cut was totally thrilling, completely thrilling.

243
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:09,000
I don't remember ever seeing Dr. King at all in New York. I don't remember any of that.

244
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:13,000
So what was your initial question?

245
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:15,000
The number of civil rights movement.

246
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:19,000
Yes. Oh, the Civil Rights Movement was very, very, very present.

247
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:36,000
And I think in simple-minded psychological terms, the Civil Rights Movement replaced what I had vicariously experienced as revolt by Jewish young people during the war.

248
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:42,000
This was like our time. This was our moment. That's what I got so electrified.

249
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:46,000
I wish I knew the name of the place. I just know where I was on.

250
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:48,000
I was on 42nd Street.

251
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:54,000
And the main library I had been at the library doing something. I don't remember what.

252
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:59,000
And I went across the street. There was a coffee shop there, and I sat down at the counter.

253
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:01,000
Isn't that ironic at the counter?

254
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:05,000
And of course, as I've told all these kids, we all smoked.

255
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:09,000
Oh my God, did we smoke like chimneys, you know, coffee?

256
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:13,000
And I remember sitting there, I opened up the paper. What?

257
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:15,000
What?

258
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:21,000
And it wasn't so much that they couldn't be served. It was that they didn't get up.

259
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:23,000
They didn't get up.

260
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:26,000
And it was just thrilling.

261
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:35,000
And now I keep saying to myself, I should go to the microphone at the 42nd Street Library and see what page it was on.

262
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:41,000
I always say page 16, page 37, I don't actually remember. But it was not page 1. I'll tell you that.

263
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:44,000
And so this is the coverage of the greens for those cities.

264
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:45,000
Yes, right.

265
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:46,000
Was there a picture?

266
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:47,000
Nope.

267
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:49,000
And just that little short one.

268
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:54,000
And you remember, in those days they called the Times the Gray Lady because it was grey, grey, grey.

269
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:56,000
They had hardly any photos.

270
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:59,000
Tiny, tiny type and ads.

271
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:03,000
And I don't remember what page. I have to find out someday.

272
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:06,000
Someday, somebody must know. It's in some history books somewhere.

273
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:07,000
Is that what page?

274
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:10,000
It's February 2nd.

275
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:14,000
Right, so the book was sitting in the first green poster in February 1st.

276
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:16,000
You were about a February 2nd.

277
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:17,000
Oh my God.

278
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:19,000
And you're electrified?

279
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:21,000
Yes, college graduate.

280
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:22,000
College graduate.

281
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:23,000
What?

282
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:24,000
College graduate.

283
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:27,000
Living at home had just graduated.

284
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:36,000
Looking around for a job, which I did, I got a short term job at the National Guardian, which was a left wing newspaper.

285
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:41,000
Being very unsettled, not knowing what I was going to do.

286
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:46,000
A lot of the girls that I knew were already married.

287
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:50,000
And some of them had become pinned.

288
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:52,000
I don't know if you know what that even is.

289
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:54,000
Do you know what that is?

290
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:56,000
To be wearing a fraternity pin.

291
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:01,000
And they were, they would wear it as close to the nipple as possible.

292
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:04,000
And these bras were like this then.

293
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:08,000
You know, like arrows, like the prow of boats.

294
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:11,000
And they would wear this thing right here.

295
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:12,000
Oh my God.

296
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:14,000
It was ridiculous.

297
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:17,000
So those people were already married.

298
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:21,000
And then half of the other people, you know, had to be engaged.

299
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:24,000
My sister got married when she was 20.

300
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:25,000
I was 20.

301
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:27,000
I was a year and a half older.

302
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:30,000
And people came to me at the wedding and said, don't worry dear.

303
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Your time will come.

304
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:33,000
And I was 21.

305
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:35,000
Were you worried?

306
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:37,000
I think I was worried.

307
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:40,000
I mean, I think, yeah, sure, I was worried.

308
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,000
I mean, if they were worried, how come I wasn't worried?

309
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:46,000
I mean, of course, I was worried, a little worried.

310
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:50,000
So I was, you know, I was at a good place.

311
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:53,000
I mean, had I had family responsibilities?

312
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:55,000
I probably never would have gone knowing me.

313
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:57,000
I would not have gone.

314
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:00,000
So finally, I found through Freddie's friend,

315
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:02,000
her girlfriend, Jocelyn.

316
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:05,000
And she was working at the choral office.

317
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:08,000
And she said, this is going to be this workshop.

318
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:11,000
So I was not brave like other people, you know, just,

319
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:14,000
I mean, I saw people for years coming south.

320
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:17,000
They would walk in the office on Raymond Street with the suitcase.

321
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:19,000
Okay, here I am.

322
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:21,000
I've just come from Pobabla.

323
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:23,000
And I remember being very arctic with them.

324
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:25,000
Like, why didn't you tell us you were coming?

325
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:27,000
And, you know, what is this?

326
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:30,000
Just popping up.

327
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,000
I would never have done that.

328
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:34,000
Never, never.

329
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:37,000
I enrolled in this workshop.

330
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:40,000
And we went to Miami Florida.

331
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:42,000
This was core.

332
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:44,000
There were a lot of people there from Louisiana.

333
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:47,000
I ended up living in Louisiana for 17 years,

334
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:51,000
but had absolutely no idea that was going to happen.

335
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:54,000
And some people who turned out to be kind of famous.

336
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:59,000
There was, oh, just died.

337
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:01,000
Rudy Lombard.

338
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:06,000
There was a white guy named Hugh Murray.

339
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:12,000
There was one of the twins, Pam, and, hmm, do.

340
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:14,000
Well, her married name was Do.

341
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:16,000
Do-E-E-Pat.

342
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:19,000
That's right, Patricia.

343
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:22,000
And, and Priscilla can't think of the last name.

344
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:25,000
Stevens, exactly.

345
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:27,000
And Angeline Butler.

346
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:30,000
Angeline Butler was in that group from Nashville.

347
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:33,000
That's right.

348
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:36,000
And we all gathered in Miami.

349
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:41,000
And actually, some of the people were pro, I mean, Angie was a pro by then.

350
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:45,000
She had been arrested several times.

351
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:48,000
And it was four months after the sit-ins.

352
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:50,000
So the sit-ins were February.

353
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:52,000
This is March, April, May, June.

354
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,000
It was June, four months after the sit-ins started.

355
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:58,000
So, how long was the workshop?

356
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:03,000
Well, the workshop, as I recall, here my memory gets a little fuzzy.

357
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:05,000
It was about two weeks.

358
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:10,000
And the idea was from the core point of view, you know,

359
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:17,000
that everybody would be trained as nonviolent organizers and go back.

360
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:23,000
But going back for core was, I mean, they were not in the rural areas at all.

361
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:28,000
And the only place in the south where they actually were was New Orleans.

362
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:31,000
So they were heavy duty northern people.

363
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:33,000
Jim Lowy was one of the people.

364
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:35,000
And he was there.

365
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:38,000
And so there were people who were never going to be working south.

366
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:39,000
They were going back north.

367
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:42,000
And I don't remember what their organizational overview was.

368
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:46,000
You know, I was, you know, just one of the people.

369
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:50,000
Looking back, now that I'm thinking about it, which I don't often,

370
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:57,000
they must have also been looking for another generation of members, supporters, fundraisers.

371
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:03,000
They probably wanted a big geographical spread as they possibly could get.

372
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:10,000
And the urban northern.

373
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:19,000
But they had this kind of branch in Louisiana.

374
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:21,000
They were strong in Louisiana.

375
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:26,000
Do you know a sense at all from that that they're trying to make in roads into the south,

376
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:29,000
especially if they're bringing this city in there?

377
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:30,000
Yes, yes.

378
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:35,000
I don't think they succeeded, but they, because their roots, their administration,

379
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:37,000
everything was in the north.

380
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:41,000
And we had some national leaders there, Marvin Rich, whatever his last name was,

381
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:43,000
which was there.

382
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:47,000
So, and I have a picture somewhere of all of these people.

383
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:51,000
So, that was amazing experience.

384
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:55,000
And do you want the story of the arrest and all of that?

385
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:58,000
Okay, so we were sitting at this restaurant, the name of which I can't remember,

386
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:00,000
but Angeline Butler remembered.

387
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:04,000
And they wouldn't serve us.

388
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:06,000
You will not be served.

389
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:08,000
I don't remember how many people, 17 maybe.

390
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:11,000
And on the way out, we started to sing.

391
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:13,000
I think I was one of the first people.

392
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:16,000
I'm happy to say that we was out on the, we started singing.

393
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:23,000
And then I realized I dawned on me that I was the only white woman in the group.

394
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:26,000
And we were on a waiter channel.

395
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:29,000
And this is what I tell these young people.

396
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:35,000
Now I say, look, you think it's only the lunch, the only lunch counters and only the buses.

397
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:39,000
So, I say, from the time you got up in the morning to the time you went to bed,

398
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:43,000
your entire life was formulated on the basis of your color.

399
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:47,000
And I go into a list which they're very shocked to hear.

400
00:32:47,000 --> 00:32:52,000
I said, of course, the jails do they care about the jails, but it didn't do it on them.

401
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:53,000
That the jails were segregated.

402
00:32:53,000 --> 00:33:02,000
And I talk about how, when I went to Atlanta, middle class black women would spend $400 for a dress.

403
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:04,000
Couldn't try on the dress.

404
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:06,000
No dressing rooms had to take it home.

405
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:08,000
Too bad, didn't fit. Too bad.

406
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:14,000
And then I noticed all these young women are nodding at me like, oh, oh, you know.

407
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:17,000
I'll talk about the dentist's office, the doctor's office.

408
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:20,000
So, here I was on the way to jail.

409
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:24,000
Okay, so it was very frightening.

410
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:30,000
And they brought me into the cell and it was at night.

411
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:33,000
So, the bed was not made.

412
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:41,000
So, there was some sort of covering and I lay on the mattress all the next morning, the women said,

413
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:43,000
you slept on that.

414
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:47,000
Oh, God, it was this poor little thing.

415
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:50,000
I don't know what I was supposed to do.

416
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:51,000
Sit up all night.

417
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:54,000
You know, I wasn't about, and it was on the upper bunk.

418
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:57,000
Oh, detail I had forgotten about till this moment.

419
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:00,000
I wasn't about to be making a bed in the middle of the night.

420
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:02,000
You know.

421
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:10,000
So, the matron came in and we all had to line up and she did not call me a niggle lover or anything like that.

422
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:14,000
But they all knew there's something peculiar about me.

423
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:17,000
She handed me this mop.

424
00:34:17,000 --> 00:34:22,000
The mop weighed about 30 pounds and mopped the floor.

425
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:30,000
Now, I believe me that housework was not my strong suit at the best of time.

426
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:35,000
So, I did something, pushed the mop around and they were all, they made ruthless fun of me these women.

427
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:41,000
Oh, my God, but I don't remember them being vicious.

428
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:51,000
And I really, I mean, aside from being petrified that I was in jail, I didn't really feel any terrible menacing.

429
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:55,000
I think they must have asked me why I was there.

430
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:58,000
And I must have said, arrested at a lunch counter.

431
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:00,000
I didn't know how to lie.

432
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:02,000
I probably said that.

433
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:03,000
And who were they?

434
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:05,000
They were check for years.

435
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:08,000
They were white, you know, white collar women.

436
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:10,000
You know, it was obvious.

437
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:15,000
You know, no money to feed the kids, no petty thieves, that kind of thing.

438
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:18,000
They shouldn't even been there to begin with.

439
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:26,000
So, after the whole day went on like this, then they called me into a meeting with the lawyer.

440
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:29,000
And they said, people are coming out.

441
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:32,000
If you want to come out, you can come out.

442
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:34,000
I guess they had gotten the bond.

443
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:37,000
They didn't want to keep us there for days and days.

444
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:41,000
And I said, yeah, I want to come out.

445
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:46,000
So, I have a picture, by the way, of me through the bars.

446
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:49,000
Through the, yeah.

447
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:56,000
Okay, well, I have to lay my hands on it now, but it's from the newspaper.

448
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:59,000
It was a newspaper article about me.

449
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:02,000
And it's me behind the screen.

450
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:04,000
You said that people were coming out.

451
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:07,000
I know that Patricia was solid.

452
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:08,000
A lot of some people, Stevens.

453
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:09,000
She stayed in.

454
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:10,000
Okay, good.

455
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:11,000
And she stayed in.

456
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:17,000
So, some of them had already, I think, the Stephens sisters sisters had already done jail in the Bay.

457
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:18,000
That's right.

458
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:19,000
They were sitting.

459
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:24,000
And so, I wondered if there's any discussion about staying in the course you have nobody to discuss it with.

460
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:26,000
No, I had nobody to discuss it with.

461
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:29,000
And I don't remember any discussion ahead of time.

462
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:34,000
Now, that would have been nice as an organizing thing to say, if you're arrested, what are we going to do?

463
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:36,000
Are we staying in nothing?

464
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:37,000
Nothing.

465
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:45,000
And now looking back, you know, there was no, I didn't expect any special treatment, but it seemed to me as an organizer.

466
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:52,000
I, for many years later, I would have noticed that, oh, there is one white woman here.

467
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:55,000
Do we need to do something special here?

468
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:59,000
Because, obviously, I was in minimal danger.

469
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:01,000
Not, I don't think I was terrible.

470
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:03,000
I wasn't in danger, then.

471
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:09,000
But it would have occurred to me if I had been an administrator, oh, maybe this is our weak link here.

472
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:14,000
And maybe that's one of the reasons they wanted to get me out, also, you know.

473
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:16,000
But they never, they didn't communicate that with me.

474
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:18,000
It was left entirely up to me.

475
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:21,000
I think Angie stayed in other people stayed in.

476
00:37:21,000 --> 00:37:27,000
But they had an administrative problem because they had this project, you know, where they're going to keep people in jail forever.

477
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:32,000
Looking back, now that I'm talking about it, it wasn't very well thought out.

478
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:34,000
I mean, I think you were going to get arrested.

479
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:40,000
I have the impression that you really weren't expecting to be arrested and then ended up being arrested.

480
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:43,000
That's why I think that's what it's sort of like over there.

481
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:46,000
Well, it's possible. It's possible.

482
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:51,000
I mean, they chose the restaurant.

483
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:55,000
They must have cased out the place first. They must have.

484
00:37:55,000 --> 00:37:57,000
So this was basically your practical, right?

485
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:00,000
You've been seeing the theory of not violence and that, you know, other action.

486
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:06,000
And they did the usual thing, you know, beforehand, you know, we lay it down on the floor, hold your head.

487
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:08,000
People would come and scream at you.

488
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:11,000
I do remember that they had us change roles.

489
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:14,000
Either you were the victim or you were the perp.

490
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:18,000
And in these little practical things, they made us the perps.

491
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:23,000
The people who were the perps had to scream every while thing they could possibly scream.

492
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:29,000
And I remember screaming getting unbelievably upset that I was standing there screaming.

493
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:33,000
And how easy it was to tell you the truth.

494
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:36,000
Oh, you know, you can stand there.

495
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:40,000
You can turn into a fascist, you know, unless you're careful.

496
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:42,000
Unless you're careful.

497
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:46,000
In that, you remember in that workshop, in any sense,

498
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:50,000
or males and females have a different role.

499
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:54,000
Is there being any concern about women being hurt and anything protected?

500
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:57,000
No. I don't remember anything like that.

501
00:38:57,000 --> 00:38:59,000
But I think I was very poor.

502
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:02,000
I was definitely a poor subject when it came to women.

503
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:06,000
I had no consciousness of myself as a woman at all.

504
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:11,000
You know, I mean, I think up until that point, up for several years afterwards, you know,

505
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:12,000
I was following along.

506
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:14,000
I've true an unorthodox path.

507
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:19,000
Nevertheless, it was expected that I was going to get married.

508
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:21,000
I was going to have children.

509
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:23,000
It was all programmed.

510
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:29,000
And this was a rather unorthodox way of going about it.

511
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:31,000
But it was nothing.

512
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:33,000
I was not saying no.

513
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:35,000
No, I didn't.

514
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:39,000
So then I didn't want to leave them.

515
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:42,000
That was when it all came over, I didn't want to leave.

516
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:50,000
So I said, I begged them to take me with them to New Orleans.

517
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:54,000
And there was a large contingent of...

518
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:57,000
That's what I mean, that they were strong in Louisiana.

519
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:00,000
Stronger, I should say, in Louisiana.

520
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:03,000
And a whole bunch of them were going back.

521
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:05,000
I stayed with somebody whose name I can't remember.

522
00:40:05,000 --> 00:40:09,000
A black woman who lived on Claiborne or near Claiborne Avenue.

523
00:40:09,000 --> 00:40:14,000
And I stayed at least a week, if not two weeks.

524
00:40:14,000 --> 00:40:19,000
And they were getting ready for the first sit-in.

525
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:21,000
Which they had not had yet.

526
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:23,000
Now that was kind of interesting.

527
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:27,000
Somebody will write us an article about that because they were...

528
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:33,000
What was the name of the black college there?

529
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:35,000
They were two.

530
00:40:35,000 --> 00:40:38,000
Xavier and Loyola, not Loyola.

531
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:41,000
Zabier.

532
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:43,000
Xavier and Xavier.

533
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:46,000
So that was kind of unusual that they had not had any sit-ins there.

534
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:49,000
They were all like, I don't know why.

535
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:52,000
Somebody knows why, but I don't know why.

536
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:54,000
Maybe they were infighting in the community.

537
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:56,000
I don't know exactly why.

538
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:00,000
So when we got there, they were definitely ready to do it.

539
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:02,000
But it was now that I'm thinking about it.

540
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:04,000
It was coming from outside.

541
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:06,000
It was coming from the core people.

542
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:09,000
It was not coming from the local students.

543
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:11,000
I mean, it was coming from here.

544
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:14,000
It was coming from this woman who I stayed with.

545
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:16,000
I lived there who were resident there.

546
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:20,000
But it was not coming from student groups as I recall.

547
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:24,000
So we met in the Y, the black Y.

548
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:28,000
And so I was making signs.

549
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:30,000
I had gone to Music and Art High School.

550
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:33,000
This is where my art career came in handy.

551
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:35,000
So I was making signs.

552
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:37,000
And then there was this...

553
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:39,000
I was one of the white people.

554
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:42,000
I was to case the...

555
00:41:42,000 --> 00:41:44,000
The Woolworths on Canal Street.

556
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:45,000
I went...

557
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:46,000
We did that.

558
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:47,000
There were several of us.

559
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:49,000
And we case the place and where it was...

560
00:41:49,000 --> 00:41:51,000
You know, what was going to happen?

561
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:54,000
And where was the lunch counter and so forth and so on.

562
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:57,000
And then my role was...

563
00:41:57,000 --> 00:42:02,000
They asked me what I do outreach into the white community.

564
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:04,000
And so I went to see this...

565
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:07,000
Rather famous priest named Joseph Fichter,

566
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:10,000
who was at Loyola University New Orleans.

567
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:13,000
Loyola University New Orleans.

568
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:18,000
And he had been very well known as a very good on racial issues.

569
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:24,000
And the Catholic Church actually was to definitely more advanced

570
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:26,000
than almost any institution there.

571
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:30,000
They had already integrated this school.

572
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:32,000
And I met him.

573
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:35,000
I told him that there were going to be sit-ins there.

574
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:36,000
The first sit-in.

575
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:37,000
And could they do anything?

576
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:39,000
And he said, yes, we will help.

577
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:41,000
We will talk about it in our...

578
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:43,000
You know, in our parishes.

579
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:44,000
We will...

580
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:47,000
We'll spread out the word very, very cooperative.

581
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:50,000
And then they sent me...

582
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:53,000
They told me to go to him and to go to the rabbi.

583
00:42:53,000 --> 00:42:54,000
One of the big rabbis.

584
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:58,000
And that's where I went to see this rabbi who kicked me out of his office.

585
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:01,000
Which I must say...

586
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:05,000
Now, in retrospect, he didn't realize what a big favor he was doing.

587
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:08,000
Because I have used that story.

588
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:10,000
55 years.

589
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:11,000
Thank you very much.

590
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:16,000
Rabbi Julian Feibelman, F-E-I-B-E-L-M-A-N.

591
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:17,000
At...

592
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:20,000
No, don't remember him at all.

593
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:26,000
And I was extremely upset when he threw me out of his office.

594
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:27,000
Really upset.

595
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:32,000
And, you know, as I said, that has stayed me in good state.

596
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:36,000
It is a Jewish activist now that this rabbi threw me out.

597
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:40,000
When the Catholic had invited me in, okay?

598
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:44,000
And I just should say parenthetically that as the years went on

599
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:50,000
and I traveled around the South, I learned what had happened to the Jews there.

600
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:55,000
And I remember one time, Bob and I drove through...

601
00:43:55,000 --> 00:43:57,000
It must have been Hayneville, Alabama.

602
00:43:57,000 --> 00:43:58,000
Am I saying it right?

603
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:01,000
Bob Zellner, my former husband.

604
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:04,000
Is it Hayneville, Alabama? Am I right?

605
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:05,000
Hayneville, Alabama?

606
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:09,000
Well, we pronounced it in Alabama.

607
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:11,000
In Lowndes County.

608
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:14,000
I don't know, maybe I'm wrong.

609
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:18,000
Well, if it's Hayneville, Alabama, then I think some of the local people...

610
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:19,000
I don't know, I have to look at...

611
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:22,000
I remember it is Hayneville, Alabama, but it's probably wrong.

612
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:26,000
And I remember going through that town.

613
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:28,000
I will never forget that town.

614
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:30,000
I don't know what it looks like now.

615
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:31,000
It looks like a movie set.

616
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:36,000
It looked just like intruder in the dust.

617
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:46,000
Or the one with Atticus, to Kilomockingberg.

618
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:49,000
And there was the town square like this.

619
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:52,000
And there were the men on their chairs, tilted back.

620
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:57,000
There were the trees with the, you know, the vines,

621
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:00,000
the finish moths, yes, hanging down.

622
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:02,000
And there was Goldberg's store.

623
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:06,000
Or if it wasn't Goldberg, it was Feinberg, it was something.

624
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:09,000
And in the middle of...

625
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:11,000
Blankety Blank, nowhere.

626
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:14,000
I would actually, am I allowed to use bad language on this?

627
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:15,000
Probably not.

628
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:16,000
Not.

629
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:17,000
Okay.

630
00:45:17,000 --> 00:45:19,000
Okay.

631
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:22,000
So, I then...

632
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:23,000
Okay.

633
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:24,000
Alright.

634
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:28,000
So then I began, as the years went on, I understood,

635
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:32,000
how they had gotten there.

636
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:35,000
You know, their role was not enviable.

637
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:38,000
They were not accepted by anybody.

638
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:41,000
They were always trying desperately to be white.

639
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:43,000
They were never secure.

640
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:48,000
They were like the Chinese store owner in Greenwood,

641
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:52,000
who was the same way, trying so hard to be white.

642
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:56,000
And he would never be white, no matter what he did.

643
00:45:56,000 --> 00:45:58,000
And I don't know.

644
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:02,000
Someday, maybe somebody will write some books about them.

645
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:04,000
And maybe they have.

646
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:08,000
Or, um, another conversation that when you were in Miami,

647
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:13,000
all the workshops that a lot of people were telling you about SNCC.

648
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:14,000
Oh, yes.

649
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:17,000
Oh, no, no, absolutely.

650
00:46:17,000 --> 00:46:19,000
Absolutely.

651
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:22,000
I mean, I realized while I was there,

652
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:24,000
and then when I...

653
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:28,000
in desperation, I had to go to New Orleans that I had found something

654
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:31,000
that I wanted to come back.

655
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:33,000
I knew I wanted to come back.

656
00:46:33,000 --> 00:46:35,000
And so I started asking people, I said,

657
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:37,000
well, what do you advise?

658
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:40,000
And Bernard Lafayette was in this group.

659
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:42,000
And it was Bernard, who said to me,

660
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:43,000
SNCC.

661
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:45,000
Go to SNCC.

662
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:48,000
And so I sort of stored that away in my mind.

663
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:52,000
SNCC was... I didn't know what to think about it.

664
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:55,000
So I was in New Orleans, I guess, for a couple of weeks.

665
00:46:55,000 --> 00:46:57,000
And then we had the famous sit-ins.

666
00:46:57,000 --> 00:46:59,000
The sit-ins were spectacular.

667
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:01,000
I must say they really were.

668
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:04,000
And I was...

669
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:09,000
One of my assignments was to drive the car.

670
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:12,000
So...

671
00:47:12,000 --> 00:47:15,000
to keep track of what I'm saying, Emily,

672
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:20,000
skip a hit and say something about cars.

673
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:23,000
It's only after we did the book,

674
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:26,000
the hands on the Freedom Plow,

675
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:30,000
that I realized that SNCC had no resources,

676
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:35,000
except for one car.

677
00:47:35,000 --> 00:47:39,000
And that it became a big issue.

678
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:42,000
Who controlled the cars?

679
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:46,000
And who drove the cars?

680
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:50,000
So young women are very surprised to hear that

681
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:55,000
if you were in an intergender group,

682
00:47:55,000 --> 00:47:57,000
a woman never drove a car.

683
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:00,000
If a man was in the group and could drive a car.

684
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:05,000
Never, like, never.

685
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:09,000
And our book has many wonderful stories in it

686
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:12,000
about cars and who controlled the cars.

687
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:16,000
And the best one is Zoharah Simmons,

688
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:19,000
who was a project director,

689
00:48:19,000 --> 00:48:21,000
and controlled...

690
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:25,000
The car was controlled by the previous project director,

691
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:27,000
who then left.

692
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:31,000
And she felt it came within her purview,

693
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:36,000
as everybody else did, except this guy wanted to take the car with him.

694
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:39,000
So then I realized cars, cars,

695
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:41,000
loom very big.

696
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:45,000
And you talk about our great characters,

697
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:46,000
like Stokely.

698
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:49,000
Stokely, in my mind, is inseparable from a car.

699
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:52,000
And we had these legendary drivers.

700
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:55,000
People would talk about so-and-so,

701
00:48:55,000 --> 00:48:58,000
drove, I mean, they drove like backs out of hell,

702
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:00,000
but they were...

703
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:03,000
But they must have been fantastic drivers.

704
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:06,000
And María Varela has a story in there,

705
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:08,000
in Hansen, where she's driving,

706
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:12,000
trying to escape the clan at 110 miles an hour,

707
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:18,000
cars and loom very heavily under the story.

708
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:20,000
Anyway, I was...

709
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:21,000
So...

710
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:24,000
It's something not very long ago about how Stokely will come into the group.

711
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:25,000
Oh, yes.

712
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:27,000
Well, Stokely was...

713
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:29,000
He was head of the second district.

714
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:32,000
The whole Mississippi was divided into district.

715
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:35,000
And his district was one of the really hopping,

716
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:38,000
popping districts, because it was not only Greenwood,

717
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:40,000
it was...

718
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:45,000
Tallahatchie County was these truly unbelievably terrible places.

719
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:48,000
Ruleville was in the second district.

720
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:51,000
I don't know if Greenville was in the second district.

721
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:53,000
Oh, Greenville.

722
00:49:53,000 --> 00:49:56,000
And so he was with me making the rounds all the time.

723
00:49:56,000 --> 00:49:58,000
He was unbelievable character.

724
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:01,000
He was about to six with three, skinny like this.

725
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:06,000
It's very, very handsome, very charismatic, ever.

726
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:09,000
And he would drive in.

727
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:11,000
We always knew it was him.

728
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:12,000
He would drive in.

729
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:15,000
You know, but his feet on the brakes,

730
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:17,000
the gravel would be flying.

731
00:50:17,000 --> 00:50:20,000
Get out of the car.

732
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:23,000
Smooth his clothes down.

733
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:26,000
He was unbelievable character.

734
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:27,000
Unbelievable.

735
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:29,000
So that's the way he drove.

736
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:32,000
Driving was very important and actually driving was,

737
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:37,000
because your life could depend on how well people drove.

738
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:40,000
And so women sell them if they ever drove.

739
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:43,000
And back to this story, I was supposed to drive.

740
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:44,000
Now I am a new...

741
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:46,000
You know, in New Orleans.

742
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:49,000
Now we're back in the city in 1960.

743
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:52,000
And I was supposed to drive.

744
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:54,000
And I was a terrible driver.

745
00:50:54,000 --> 00:50:58,000
I had learned to drive late in life in New York City.

746
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:01,000
Well, none of us had a car.

747
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:03,000
But I did have a license.

748
00:51:03,000 --> 00:51:06,000
And evidently, I don't remember why nobody else could drive.

749
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:08,000
I had no idea.

750
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:11,000
So after the event, they had me driving

751
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:12,000
and we almost got killed.

752
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:14,000
I'm sure we were going around.

753
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:16,000
We were going around a traffic circle,

754
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:18,000
which later on living there 17 years,

755
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:21,000
I went around all the time.

756
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:23,000
I had no idea what I was doing.

757
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:25,000
And everybody was screaming in the car.

758
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:28,000
Oh, what are you doing?

759
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:32,000
We never should have let you drive.

760
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,000
Oh, my God.

761
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:38,000
So it was very dramatic because Hugh Murray's father

762
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:42,000
had been driving along in Harahan, Louisiana.

763
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:45,000
I think they were from Harahan, Louisiana.

764
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:49,000
And he heard on the radio that a sit-in was going on

765
00:51:49,000 --> 00:51:52,000
and that there was a white man in the group.

766
00:51:53,000 --> 00:51:55,000
And I think they must have said his name,

767
00:51:55,000 --> 00:51:57,000
or he knew it was his son.

768
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:00,000
So he came storming into the wallworths

769
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:04,000
through the cops, through, they roped it off,

770
00:52:04,000 --> 00:52:09,000
and literally grabbed Hugh and dragged him off the seat

771
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:12,000
and dragged him away.

772
00:52:12,000 --> 00:52:16,000
And Hugh, actually, I don't know if it was ever the same again,

773
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:18,000
I met him a few times over the years.

774
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:21,000
He was kind of an eccentric character.

775
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:25,000
The white people who lived there, the southern white people,

776
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:27,000
they had very little support.

777
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:32,000
And this was a big thing, it was covered in its times,

778
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:33,000
Piccoyoon.

779
00:52:33,000 --> 00:52:35,000
And I don't really know.

780
00:52:35,000 --> 00:52:37,000
I think he's written something.

781
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:39,000
If I'm not sure, you might have written something.

782
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:41,000
Hugh Murray.

783
00:52:41,000 --> 00:52:44,000
So then I went home and I said,

784
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:46,000
oh, well, SNCC is the place to go.

785
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:47,000
Bernhardt sits Snick.

786
00:52:47,000 --> 00:52:49,000
Other people had said Snick.

787
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:52,000
Corb was not an attractive thing to me.

788
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:58,000
Well, I suppose there were, first of all,

789
00:52:58,000 --> 00:53:03,000
there were very few what I would call later came to call local people.

790
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:06,000
Even though the Stephens sisters, I think, were from South Carolina

791
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:08,000
or North Carolina, from Florida.

792
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:10,000
Oh, that's right, from Florida.

793
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:14,000
There were several people from New Orleans there,

794
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:16,000
but a lot of people from New York.

795
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:18,000
I don't know, I just didn't want to be in New York.

796
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:21,000
You know, I just felt it was a southern thing.

797
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:23,000
I don't even know how much I thought about it.

798
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:25,000
But it wasn't attracted to me.

799
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:27,000
Definitely was not.

800
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:34,000
And so all through that year, I was writing letters to SNCC.

801
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:37,000
And little did I know they were throwing them in the garbage.

802
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:40,000
There was nobody there to even open them.

803
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:43,000
And I just thought, well, they're not interested.

804
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:46,000
You know, oh, what did I know?

805
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:49,000
I finally got a job, for my first job,

806
00:53:49,000 --> 00:53:54,000
after I came back with this horrible job doing proofreading

807
00:53:54,000 --> 00:54:01,000
for a scientific magazine, proofreading equations.

808
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:04,000
Can you imagine anything more terrible than that?

809
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:07,000
I lasted about six months on that.

810
00:54:07,000 --> 00:54:08,000
Then I had to leave.

811
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:13,000
Then I finally got a job in the welfare department.

812
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:16,000
The welfare department was like the home for everybody there.

813
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:19,000
It didn't matter who you were, you graduated,

814
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:22,000
you had nowhere to go, you went into the welfare department.

815
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:24,000
And I was a welfare investigator,

816
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:28,000
which was another story we'll get to some other year.

817
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:32,000
And then, by a peculiar fluke,

818
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:35,000
because life is made of all these flops,

819
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:39,000
it turns out that a black guy had been hired

820
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:42,000
at the Southern Regional Council.

821
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:47,000
And his name was James A. Moss, M-O-S-S.

822
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:50,000
He had been a professor at Queens College

823
00:54:50,000 --> 00:54:53,000
when I was the editor of the student newspaper.

824
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:59,000
And he was the only black professor in the entire school.

825
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:02,000
And his contract was not renewed.

826
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:07,000
And he came to me and told me his story.

827
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:09,000
And I was totally outraged.

828
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:12,000
And I wanted to do a story about it.

829
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:15,000
But he wouldn't let me. He was afraid.

830
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:19,000
And he felt he would never be hired anywhere else.

831
00:55:19,000 --> 00:55:21,000
And he left.

832
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:24,000
Do you know why it would come to you about the story?

833
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:26,000
Yes, because...

834
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:29,000
Yes, I think he wanted some emotional support.

835
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:32,000
And I think I was the editor of the paper.

836
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:34,000
I was known as a lefty.

837
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:36,000
And I think that's why he came to me.

838
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:38,000
Otherwise, I would never have known.

839
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:42,000
So one of the many, many places that I wrote to

840
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:45,000
to get a job was the Southern Regional Council.

841
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:48,000
And here, James Moss had just been hired

842
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:50,000
as the research director.

843
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:52,000
And he saw my letter.

844
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:54,000
See how life is so?

845
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:56,000
And he said, oh, I know her.

846
00:55:56,000 --> 00:55:58,000
I hire her.

847
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:00,000
So in three weeks, I was down there.

848
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:03,000
From the time that he got the letter.

849
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:04,000
I was down there.

850
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:06,000
I said, okay, everybody, I'm going.

851
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:09,000
And I said to my parents, who are they're probably very happy

852
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:10,000
to get rid of me.

853
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:13,000
And my mother, I remember, my mother didn't want me to go,

854
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:15,000
but she helped me pack a trunk.

855
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:18,000
A trunk, I took a trunk down there.

856
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:19,000
I took sheets.

857
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:21,000
I took silverware.

858
00:56:21,000 --> 00:56:23,000
I don't know what...

859
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:25,000
You're going to marry this as a regional council.

860
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:28,000
I was going to marry the Southern movement

861
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:31,000
is what I was going to do.

862
00:56:31,000 --> 00:56:34,000
And so, yes.

863
00:56:34,000 --> 00:56:38,000
So I went down there and I became a research associate

864
00:56:38,000 --> 00:56:40,000
with they called in.

865
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:43,000
And they actually put me to very good use

866
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:46,000
because I am the one who did the research

867
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:50,000
for that Southern Regional Council report,

868
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:54,000
which was about the first 18 months of the Civil Rights movement,

869
00:56:54,000 --> 00:56:58,000
of the SID and movement.

870
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:01,000
Heavily edited by Leslie Dunbar, of course,

871
00:57:01,000 --> 00:57:04,000
and I think appropriately so.

872
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:08,000
But I am the one who went through all the newspaper clippings

873
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:11,000
and everything, added things and totally them

874
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:15,000
and blah, blah, blah, made up all the categories, figured out, you know.

875
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:17,000
And it was really an impressive thing.

876
00:57:17,000 --> 00:57:20,000
And when they issued it, I remember very well.

877
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:22,000
It ended up on the front page of the New York Times.

878
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:24,000
This report, not my name, of course.

879
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:25,000
I didn't exist.

880
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:29,000
My name was not on this thing at all.

881
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:34,000
As the style of those days, you know, research people, you know.

882
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:36,000
They did the work.

883
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:40,000
They wrote it and they were gone to history from history.

884
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:43,000
So that was very useful.

885
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:50,000
And then, and I lived on the white side of town.

886
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:56,000
I lived on Peachtree Street, one of the many Peachtree streets.

887
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:00,000
And SRC was an interracial organization.

888
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:03,000
So we went many places together when we could.

889
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:06,000
I lived the double life.

890
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:10,000
I went on the white side and I went on the black side as well.

891
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:12,000
So what was the white to work?

892
00:58:12,000 --> 00:58:15,000
You said you were sure of one of the white side in the black side of town?

893
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:16,000
Yes.

894
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:21,000
Well, I must say I had some guilty moments, but it didn't stop me from working on the white side.

895
00:58:21,000 --> 00:58:28,000
I didn't really have a way of getting to the black side.

896
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:35,000
And often the black people came to my house on the white side after dark.

897
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:39,000
And looking back, I mean, weren't they ashamed?

898
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:40,000
Wasn't I ashamed?

899
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:42,000
I mean, really, was overt.

900
00:58:42,000 --> 00:58:44,000
Oh, it was nighttime?

901
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:45,000
You even got her house.

902
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:46,000
Good nighttime.

903
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:47,000
What is that?

904
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:48,000
Did you talk about it?

905
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:53,000
No, I mean, I remember black people, friends of mine, who worked there.

906
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:55,000
This was an interracial organization.

907
00:58:55,000 --> 00:58:58,000
And it was just taken as a matter of course.

908
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:05,000
Well, of course, you know, she lives on the white side, so we have to go make sure that her neighbors can't see.

909
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:11,000
I remember going to places that I knew my black colleagues couldn't go to.

910
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:13,000
I wasn't easy about that.

911
00:59:13,000 --> 00:59:18,000
I only had one white friend that I had met other than Southern Regional Council.

912
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:21,000
And of course, she had nothing to do with the civil rights movement.

913
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:23,000
So she was the one, oh, let's go here.

914
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:24,000
Let's go there.

915
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:25,000
Sorry.

916
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:28,000
What happened when you go to the black side?

917
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:33,000
Oh, on the black side, it was always all we're going to be arrested.

918
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:36,000
Except when we went to a black place.

919
00:59:36,000 --> 00:59:40,000
You know, it's very hard to...

920
00:59:41,000 --> 00:59:43,000
This is what I tell these kids.

921
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:50,000
As I try to put your mind in a place where you're going to a dangerous neighborhood.

922
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:53,000
I said, what does that mean when people say you're going to a dangerous neighborhood now?

923
00:59:53,000 --> 00:59:56,000
Well, of course, it means a black neighborhood, a Latino neighborhood.

924
00:59:56,000 --> 01:00:01,000
I said with us, it was the white neighborhood that was the dangerous neighborhood.

925
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:05,000
And so when we went in the black community, we were completely...

926
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:08,000
completely say, completely say.

927
01:00:08,000 --> 01:00:13,000
White people, white people, you know, I don't know what that means to a psychologist.

928
01:00:13,000 --> 01:00:15,000
Would have some interesting insights.

929
01:00:15,000 --> 01:00:18,000
You know, what do you look at when you look in the mirror?

930
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:21,000
You know, you're saying to yourself, well, I'm one of them.

931
01:00:21,000 --> 01:00:24,000
But no, I'm not one of them.

932
01:00:24,000 --> 01:00:30,000
And then Jane came to work at Jane Bond, came to work.

933
01:00:30,000 --> 01:00:32,000
And we liked each other a lot, right away.

934
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:35,000
And she was dying to move out of her house.

935
01:00:35,000 --> 01:00:41,000
She had been a graduate student in Indiana or somewhere, coming back.

936
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:43,000
She didn't want to live at home.

937
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:52,000
I was able to find some reason to be on the block side.

938
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:59,000
I mean, in those days to live alone as a woman, getting an apartment, was not easy.

939
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:02,000
And very few people did it.

940
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:07,000
And for me to have gone into the black side, I don't even know if anybody would have rented to me.

941
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:10,000
I don't know, but I didn't even try.

942
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:17,000
So then Jane and I set up household at 2222, tell her street.

943
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:23,000
Which, by the way, the last time I was in California, Jane and I went to see.

944
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:26,000
I mean, not when I was in California.

945
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:32,000
When I was in Atlanta, Mary King took me to tell her street.

946
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:36,000
And I told Jane about it when I saw her in California.

947
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:41,000
And we lived there for a year and a half.

948
01:01:41,000 --> 01:01:46,000
So I think I might have met Jane before I met Julian.

949
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:49,000
And all this time I was in S.O.C.

950
01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:53,000
And people would come in regularly, visitors, other countries.

951
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:56,000
And they'd say, oh, and here we're having a meeting here in Bubba.

952
01:01:56,000 --> 01:01:58,000
And now we're going to SNCC.

953
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:00,000
I knew perfectly well where SNCC was.

954
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:05,000
I had tried to work for them, but they had, you know, not responded.

955
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:09,000
And they were literally 20 minutes away by foot.

956
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:12,000
And I couldn't get there.

957
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:16,000
And I was reading about all of these people in the newspaper.

958
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:20,000
They were part of the people that I was making my report about.

959
01:02:20,000 --> 01:02:28,000
And among others, I kept seeing this name, this name, you know, Bob Zellner.

960
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:34,000
And I thought to myself, what is this Jewish boy doing running around here?

961
01:02:34,000 --> 01:02:36,000
His father was a minister.

962
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:40,000
So I had no idea who he was.

963
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:45,000
And finally, finally, there was this Swedish journalist,

964
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:48,000
named Pair Lorsen.

965
01:02:48,000 --> 01:02:51,000
And he came, it was in October.

966
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:54,000
And he said, I'm going to SNCC now.

967
01:02:54,000 --> 01:02:56,000
How do I get there, Bubba?

968
01:02:56,000 --> 01:02:58,000
I said, I'm going with you.

969
01:02:58,000 --> 01:03:01,000
And I finally worked up the courage.

970
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:03,000
Five months had took me.

971
01:03:03,000 --> 01:03:08,000
So did you start working for SRC like summer, 16th?

972
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:10,000
It's June of 61.

973
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:11,000
June 61?

974
01:03:11,000 --> 01:03:17,000
And I went over to SNCC the first time in October of 61.

975
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:18,000
Good timing.

976
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:22,000
Good timing, because James Forman had been there a month.

977
01:03:22,000 --> 01:03:25,000
If I had gone there two months earlier, they would have been nothing.

978
01:03:25,000 --> 01:03:29,000
I would never have known who knows when I would have gone back.

979
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:32,000
So I don't remember what happened to Pair Lorsen.

980
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:33,000
I don't know what happened.

981
01:03:33,000 --> 01:03:37,000
Then my next memory is meeting James Forman.

982
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:46,000
And that became this momentous thing that he said to me.

983
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:52,000
So I remember he shook my hand and he said, can you type?

984
01:03:52,000 --> 01:03:55,000
And I said, yes.

985
01:03:55,000 --> 01:03:58,000
And he said, good, we need you.

986
01:03:58,000 --> 01:03:59,000
Okay?

987
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:05,000
Now later that became deconstructed by feminists as the most terrible thing a man could say.

988
01:04:05,000 --> 01:04:12,000
And I have said many times, I was beyond thrilled that he asked me if I could type.

989
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:14,000
I was so happy I could type.

990
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:20,000
But then I knew that my ability to function in the South was limited.

991
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:21,000
Okay?

992
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:23,000
Putting it mildly.

993
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:25,000
First of all, I was a woman.

994
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:27,000
Second of all, I was a white woman.

995
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:31,000
White woman equal death to black men.

996
01:04:31,000 --> 01:04:37,000
Third, I was from the North.

997
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:40,000
What else was I going to do?

998
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:41,000
Okay?

999
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:51,000
This is why I later had very little sympathy with the poor white women who felt that their skills were not being developed enough.

1000
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:54,000
So I said, yes, I can type.

1001
01:04:54,000 --> 01:04:57,000
And he right away put me to work typing.

1002
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:00,000
And then it wasn't initially the same day.

1003
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:03,000
It was probably a couple of weeks later.

1004
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:08,000
I went up to him and I said, you know, woman, I can write also.

1005
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:11,000
And maybe I said to him, I was the editor of my paper.

1006
01:05:11,000 --> 01:05:16,000
I don't remember if I even said, and he said, good.

1007
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:20,000
I'm going to put you to work with Julian.

1008
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:27,000
So I think probably by December, November December, I was already had met Julian.

1009
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:31,000
And maybe Jane and I started working living together a little bit later.

1010
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:33,000
I'm not sure exactly.

1011
01:05:33,000 --> 01:05:34,000
And Julian was Jane.

1012
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:36,000
Julian Bond.

1013
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:38,000
And James brother.

1014
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:46,000
And we started right away working on the student boys right away.

1015
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:55,000
And this is where James Forman's, you know, great genius was that he was walking around with this switchboard in his head.

1016
01:05:55,000 --> 01:05:59,000
And of course, I say switchboard here, but young people don't even know what that is.

1017
01:05:59,000 --> 01:06:06,000
You know, it's a board with holes in it and you put the screws into the right place, the plugs into the right place.

1018
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:08,000
He knew everything.

1019
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:13,000
He was walking around. He knew the whole organization was laid out in his mind.

1020
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:18,000
And it was kind of 3D version.

1021
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:20,000
He knew we need people here.

1022
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:22,000
Oh, we need people to do that.

1023
01:06:22,000 --> 01:06:24,000
We need people to do this.

1024
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:28,000
And when I said what I could do, he just instantly knew.

1025
01:06:28,000 --> 01:06:34,000
I mean, literally he didn't sit down thinking, I mean, he knew right away.

1026
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:38,000
Yes, you can type good because we have people coming from the field.

1027
01:06:38,000 --> 01:06:41,000
They need to write affidavits.

1028
01:06:41,000 --> 01:06:44,000
We need to do this. We need you to type.

1029
01:06:44,000 --> 01:06:46,000
That's mostly what I remember typing.

1030
01:06:46,000 --> 01:06:51,000
But it got so in the later years that he would hand me his mail.

1031
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:53,000
And he would say, he'd hand me a whole letter.

1032
01:06:53,000 --> 01:06:56,000
He'd say, no.

1033
01:06:56,000 --> 01:06:58,000
I wrote the whole letter.

1034
01:06:58,000 --> 01:06:59,000
I said no.

1035
01:06:59,000 --> 01:07:03,000
And then he'd sign it. Or he'd say, tell them next week.

1036
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:05,000
I mean, he would say the briefest possible thing.

1037
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:07,000
And I would write his mail.

1038
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:08,000
Write his letter.

1039
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:11,000
So he would just leave it up to you to figure out what to say to people.

1040
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:12,000
Yeah.

1041
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:14,000
But he told me what to say.

1042
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:15,000
He told you...

1043
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:17,000
He told me the essence.

1044
01:07:17,000 --> 01:07:20,000
The question is denied. The question is accepted.

1045
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:22,000
I mean, whatever it was.

1046
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:25,000
And I wrote four paragraphs, you know.

1047
01:07:25,000 --> 01:07:27,000
And I talked about SNCC.

1048
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:29,000
And I wrote about SNCC and everything.

1049
01:07:29,000 --> 01:07:34,000
Can you explain for people who may not know what you meant about white women in black men?

1050
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:37,000
Oh, yeah.

1051
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:42,000
Well, especially in the rural areas, but in the cities also.

1052
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:54,000
The deadly combination for reasons of psychotic behavior in the white community was the combination of a white woman and a black man.

1053
01:07:54,000 --> 01:08:04,000
And by then, black men had been charged, at least for more than 100 years with raping white women.

1054
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:11,000
And I had experienced in my youth some very famous cases like Willie McGee,

1055
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:20,000
cases of people who were lynched from jail, and usually because they were accused of having raped a white woman.

1056
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:33,000
And it's possible that maybe some rapes did occur somewhere along the line, but the famous cases were, in fact, white women and black men who had had relationships.

1057
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:45,000
And then for some reason, the white woman betrayed the black man, either out of fear herself or being forced by her family or whatever.

1058
01:08:45,000 --> 01:08:50,000
And Willie McGee was one of those cases where he had a long-term relationship with this white woman.

1059
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:55,000
And then they were the charged rape and he ended up being lynched.

1060
01:08:55,000 --> 01:08:58,000
Thank you so much, actually.

1061
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:03,000
Wasn't he taken out of the jail?

1062
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:05,000
I think that was something.

1063
01:09:05,000 --> 01:09:06,000
But maybe that was something else.

1064
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:08,000
Or maybe with Mack Charles Parker.

1065
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:09,000
Oh, maybe with Mack Charles Parker.

1066
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:11,000
Okay, they're both in Mississippi.

1067
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:15,000
And they both grew up dead because of their relationship.

1068
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:18,000
Maybe Willie McGee, yeah.

1069
01:09:18,000 --> 01:09:22,000
Okay, thank you.

1070
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:28,000
So anyway, in the rural areas, we were anathema, white women were anathema.

1071
01:09:28,000 --> 01:09:38,000
And, you know, our book is full of examples about just walking along the road with a black man, could mean that he would die.

1072
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:39,000
He would die.

1073
01:09:39,000 --> 01:09:49,000
So you had in your mind, I mean, I think for white women who didn't deal with this, they were in super denial, super denial.

1074
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:56,000
And especially, I never went to Southwest Georgia by the way, but according to the stories that we've told, and the book,

1075
01:09:56,000 --> 01:10:00,000
I mean, Charles Sherrod was an maniac about this.

1076
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:08,000
Charles Sherrod, I mean, viewed white women as sort of charges that were about to be detonated, you know.

1077
01:10:08,000 --> 01:10:15,000
And very strict rules, you can't go past this street for a week, you can't do this, you can't do that.

1078
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:22,000
And to make sure they didn't wander off somewhere and end up getting somebody in severe trouble.

1079
01:10:22,000 --> 01:10:31,000
So tell Charles Sherrod was a mixed project director in Southwest Georgia, and Southwest Georgia was unusual in some of the next projects because it was explicitly racial.

1080
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:34,000
He recruited white sandblacks to work.

1081
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:36,000
Right.

1082
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:42,000
Can you tell us what, can you describe Jim Forman and Grant?

1083
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:52,000
Well, I'm going to get weepy here because they're my special ones, and they're both gone now.

1084
01:10:52,000 --> 01:10:56,000
Jim was an amazing, amazing person.

1085
01:10:56,000 --> 01:11:10,000
I really think that historians who write about him, who didn't know him, and who didn't interview people who knew him, have misconstrued his character.

1086
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:16,000
First of all, he was, he didn't suffer fools gladly, number one.

1087
01:11:16,000 --> 01:11:22,000
He was highly intelligent, I mean extremely intelligent.

1088
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:26,000
He was very cultured, he was a French speaker, he spoke French.

1089
01:11:26,000 --> 01:11:33,000
He read books from Africa before anybody ever heard of Africa.

1090
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:39,000
But he had very few, what they call common social skills.

1091
01:11:39,000 --> 01:11:49,000
He didn't chat, he was not a chatter, he was not an esquester, he was not somebody, he was not going to sit there and pass the time of day.

1092
01:11:49,000 --> 01:11:54,000
He got to the heart of things, he got to the meat of things.

1093
01:11:54,000 --> 01:11:58,000
He invented the concept of friends of.

1094
01:11:58,000 --> 01:12:07,000
And now this is a concept that has been replicated all over the world, forget all of the United States, all over the world.

1095
01:12:07,000 --> 01:12:18,000
He knew in his mind, I've described the switchboard in his mind, but he also, here was Atlanta, and everything else was this wheel.

1096
01:12:18,000 --> 01:12:22,000
Atlanta was the hub, it was the wheel.

1097
01:12:23,000 --> 01:12:34,000
He invented the concept of support groups which did not do policy, they did not make policy.

1098
01:12:34,000 --> 01:12:37,000
It was the center that made the policy.

1099
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:44,000
The support groups had the option of supporting or not supporting, but they did not have any other option.

1100
01:12:45,000 --> 01:12:57,000
And he, and now Miss Baker was really responsible for keeping SNCC autonomous, but she did it bad, she was protected, not protected.

1101
01:12:57,000 --> 01:13:03,000
Her work was extended by James Forman, and James Forman insisted on that.

1102
01:13:03,000 --> 01:13:05,000
Can we stop for a second?

1103
01:13:06,000 --> 01:13:22,000
Okay, so James Forman, I'm sure it was his idea that all of these field secretaries would come off the field, the field being everything but the main office, writing these affidavits, what he called affidavits.

1104
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:30,000
Now they weren't legal affidavits in any sense, they were statements basically, and that's what I did as a volunteer.

1105
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:36,000
People would come off the field, they would sit next to me, and I would type, and they would speak.

1106
01:13:36,000 --> 01:13:41,000
And at the time I was a very fierce type, this very inaccurate type of person.

1107
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:44,000
And inaccurate.

1108
01:13:44,000 --> 01:13:51,000
And if I made a mistake, I didn't stop, I didn't correct, I just put an X on it and just kept going.

1109
01:13:51,000 --> 01:13:58,000
So I am able to tell what I typed now, 50 years later, because nobody else was sloppy like it.

1110
01:13:58,000 --> 01:14:05,000
But I was really fast, so I could type as fast as somebody could speak.

1111
01:14:05,000 --> 01:14:09,000
And then he sent them off to Robert F. Kennedy.

1112
01:14:09,000 --> 01:14:20,000
And this is what's going on now, and what the idea was that there was enough on the books already in the 1957 Civil Rights Act, where all these registrars could have been sitting in jail,

1113
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:23,000
all of this time.

1114
01:14:23,000 --> 01:14:26,000
Voter registration.

1115
01:14:26,000 --> 01:14:29,000
People in charge.

1116
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:31,000
And we kept sending them off.

1117
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:34,000
Do we want you to be aware of that?

1118
01:14:34,000 --> 01:14:39,000
And I don't even remember where the letters are, the letters are rolled in the SNCC papers, you know, I'm sure.

1119
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:42,000
That was one of the things I did.

1120
01:14:42,000 --> 01:14:49,000
He didn't have a small talk, but when he made a human contact with me,

1121
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:52,000
it was like a laser beam.

1122
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:56,000
He was, I found him very, very attractive.

1123
01:14:56,000 --> 01:15:01,000
And a very, you know, not a typical way.

1124
01:15:01,000 --> 01:15:03,000
He had a wonderful smile.

1125
01:15:03,000 --> 01:15:08,000
As a dentist's daughter, I noticed everybody's teeth without fail.

1126
01:15:08,000 --> 01:15:10,000
He had wonderful teeth.

1127
01:15:10,000 --> 01:15:11,000
He smiled.

1128
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:17,000
And he had a good sense of humor, but he rarely, if ever, he didn't initiate the humor.

1129
01:15:17,000 --> 01:15:20,000
I think he appreciated people's humor.

1130
01:15:20,000 --> 01:15:23,000
And he was constantly exasperated.

1131
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:26,000
And he never, he never hid that at all.

1132
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:32,000
And his famous gesture, you know, with people with talk, he would go like this, his meant,

1133
01:15:32,000 --> 01:15:36,000
wind it up, wind it up.

1134
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:46,000
So I had a couple of narrow escapes when he was present, which is, of course, one of the many reasons I loved him so much.

1135
01:15:46,000 --> 01:15:54,000
Once we were in Greenwood, MS, not the summer of 1964, the summer before that.

1136
01:15:54,000 --> 01:16:00,000
And it was the occasion of Bob Dylan and the folk festival.

1137
01:16:00,000 --> 01:16:10,000
And on the way out, there were two or three cars, interracial cars, and we were all stopped by the cops.

1138
01:16:10,000 --> 01:16:13,000
It was at night.

1139
01:16:13,000 --> 01:16:17,000
And it was on or near a railroad track.

1140
01:16:17,000 --> 01:16:19,000
That's all I remember.

1141
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:26,000
And the cops made us, everybody get out, and we had to put our hands up on the hood of the car.

1142
01:16:26,000 --> 01:16:30,000
And he handled it.

1143
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:35,000
I don't remember what he said, with very calm, very, very calm.

1144
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:42,000
And I don't know what they said to him, and he dealt with it.

1145
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:44,000
And I felt about him.

1146
01:16:44,000 --> 01:16:46,000
That had total confidence in him.

1147
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:57,000
That's why I bitterly reject some of these historians saying that he was, uh, uh, unstrung in some way or something.

1148
01:16:57,000 --> 01:17:03,000
When I dealt with him, when he, we were in extremis.

1149
01:17:03,000 --> 01:17:06,000
His instinct was absolutely right.

1150
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:09,000
He was never, he wasn't provocative.

1151
01:17:09,000 --> 01:17:11,000
He was very dignified.

1152
01:17:11,000 --> 01:17:15,000
He was very, um, contained, self-contained.

1153
01:17:15,000 --> 01:17:17,000
He didn't pop off. He didn't scream.

1154
01:17:17,000 --> 01:17:23,000
He didn't do anything like that, as it has been portrayed.

1155
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:26,000
I had truly total confidence.

1156
01:17:26,000 --> 01:17:29,000
If he said to me, it's okay to do this.

1157
01:17:29,000 --> 01:17:32,000
Go walk out here and go, of course, that's street.

1158
01:17:32,000 --> 01:17:34,000
And there's a car coming, but I know you're all right.

1159
01:17:34,000 --> 01:17:36,000
I probably would have done it.

1160
01:17:36,000 --> 01:17:38,000
I just had total confidence in him.

1161
01:17:38,000 --> 01:17:40,000
So that was one time.

1162
01:17:40,000 --> 01:17:52,000
And then in Danbo, when we were almost all killed again, uh, at a demonstration when they were getting ready to hose us down and beat us up, he, he saved us.

1163
01:17:52,000 --> 01:17:56,000
He realized that we were, he realized it was going to be a disaster.

1164
01:17:56,000 --> 01:18:05,000
And he got up and he went to the police chief and he said, you know, do you realize what's going to happen here?

1165
01:18:05,000 --> 01:18:08,000
I think those were his actual words.

1166
01:18:08,000 --> 01:18:11,000
And behind his back, he sort of motioned us all to leave.

1167
01:18:11,000 --> 01:18:13,000
You mean this private situation?

1168
01:18:13,000 --> 01:18:26,000
Yeah. So, um, here we were in this wretched little town which was, uh, lived and died by the mill, by the Dan River Mills company.

1169
01:18:26,000 --> 01:18:33,000
And black community had been struggling and struggling there to desegregate.

1170
01:18:33,000 --> 01:18:39,000
And the community was taking a big hit and uh, SNCC went in there.

1171
01:18:39,000 --> 01:18:43,000
And he sent me up there to write a pamphlet.

1172
01:18:43,000 --> 01:18:45,000
See, that was his idea.

1173
01:18:45,000 --> 01:18:46,000
Who would think about that?

1174
01:18:46,000 --> 01:18:47,000
Writing pamphlets.

1175
01:18:47,000 --> 01:18:48,000
You see?

1176
01:18:48,000 --> 01:18:56,000
Now, when he wrote a pamphlet, the pamphlet wasn't only, oh, will we'll just do it for history's sake, even though he, he believed in that.

1177
01:18:56,000 --> 01:18:59,000
But he knew exactly what he was going to do with it.

1178
01:18:59,000 --> 01:19:06,000
He was going to print it, he was going to distribute it, he was going to send it here to the north to the depth of, I mean, he had plans.

1179
01:19:06,000 --> 01:19:08,000
He had plans, big plans.

1180
01:19:08,000 --> 01:19:15,000
Um, so we were out there on these steps.

1181
01:19:15,000 --> 01:19:17,000
Okay, can we stop for a second?

1182
01:19:17,000 --> 01:19:25,000
Because there were about 40 people out there on the steps of this horrible town hall, a city hall.

1183
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:30,000
And right across the street were all these deputized drunks and god knows who else.

1184
01:19:30,000 --> 01:19:32,000
And they had the fire hoses across.

1185
01:19:32,000 --> 01:19:35,000
I had already been knocked down by the fire hoses.

1186
01:19:35,000 --> 01:19:38,000
Um, and...

1187
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:40,000
Did not have been hospitalized?

1188
01:19:40,000 --> 01:19:42,000
Yes, people had been hospitalized.

1189
01:19:42,000 --> 01:19:44,000
It's in the previous demonstration.

1190
01:19:44,000 --> 01:19:45,000
There were two demonstrations.

1191
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:49,000
One was when we were praying by the jail.

1192
01:19:49,000 --> 01:19:58,000
And they came out and they turned the fire hoses on us and then later on, that's when I was hit over the head by this cop.

1193
01:19:58,000 --> 01:20:06,000
And that's the picture that Danny Lyon took, where Forman is sitting next to me, he's taking an affidavit.

1194
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:10,000
I am talking about being hit over the head.

1195
01:20:10,000 --> 01:20:14,000
And unfortunately, I'm sitting in this position, people think I'm posing as a model, you know.

1196
01:20:14,000 --> 01:20:17,000
But it was actually, I was holding my head.

1197
01:20:17,000 --> 01:20:18,000
That was number one.

1198
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:19,000
Number one.

1199
01:20:19,000 --> 01:20:21,000
So, how did you get hit?

1200
01:20:21,000 --> 01:20:23,000
By this cop who hit me.

1201
01:20:23,000 --> 01:20:25,000
I was on my hands and knees.

1202
01:20:25,000 --> 01:20:27,000
I weighed 106 pounds.

1203
01:20:27,000 --> 01:20:28,000
I had no purse.

1204
01:20:28,000 --> 01:20:30,000
It was disappeared.

1205
01:20:30,000 --> 01:20:31,000
I didn't have any shoes.

1206
01:20:31,000 --> 01:20:33,000
I washed away.

1207
01:20:33,000 --> 01:20:38,000
And this guy came just out of total unnecessary sadism.

1208
01:20:38,000 --> 01:20:42,000
Hit me over the head with his stick.

1209
01:20:42,000 --> 01:20:49,000
And that's when I said, you know that they say that seeing stores is an expression.

1210
01:20:49,000 --> 01:20:54,000
It's not an expression because I actually saw lights going off in my brain.

1211
01:20:54,000 --> 01:20:57,000
I'm sure that he damaged some blood vessels in my brain.

1212
01:20:57,000 --> 01:21:00,000
And that's what I was seeing.

1213
01:21:00,000 --> 01:21:03,000
So, not to be outdone where you went back.

1214
01:21:03,000 --> 01:21:05,000
And that was the other thing about SNCC.

1215
01:21:05,000 --> 01:21:07,000
You always go back.

1216
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:10,000
Wherever people are in the most danger, you go to them.

1217
01:21:10,000 --> 01:21:11,000
We like the fire department.

1218
01:21:11,000 --> 01:21:13,000
It was like the fire department.

1219
01:21:13,000 --> 01:21:18,000
And then if you're something bad happens, you go back.

1220
01:21:18,000 --> 01:21:21,000
You do something that shows that you're not afraid, that you're going to continue.

1221
01:21:21,000 --> 01:21:24,000
That was the whole SNCC methodology.

1222
01:21:24,000 --> 01:21:29,000
And that's probably why we had such a reputation for good and ill, you know.

1223
01:21:29,000 --> 01:21:35,000
That we were not, that SNCC was in temperate and hotheaded and so forth.

1224
01:21:35,000 --> 01:21:38,000
So, the going back was the community went back to City Hall.

1225
01:21:38,000 --> 01:21:42,000
And they vowed that they would stay there for, you know, day and night if necessary.

1226
01:21:42,000 --> 01:21:44,000
We lasted about eight hours.

1227
01:21:44,000 --> 01:21:48,000
My favorite memory of the last thing I said for a moment.

1228
01:21:48,000 --> 01:21:51,000
You hear we were all sitting on the steps.

1229
01:21:51,000 --> 01:21:53,000
He said, he must have thought himself.

1230
01:21:53,000 --> 01:21:57,000
These people are going to go stir crazy just sitting there all day.

1231
01:21:57,000 --> 01:21:59,000
I have to do something.

1232
01:21:59,000 --> 01:22:04,000
He said, now we're going to have a workshop about black history.

1233
01:22:04,000 --> 01:22:06,000
And he would open down this day.

1234
01:22:06,000 --> 01:22:08,000
Now, who was Harriet Tubman?

1235
01:22:08,000 --> 01:22:10,000
Tell me who was Harriet Tubman.

1236
01:22:10,000 --> 01:22:11,000
And people would answer.

1237
01:22:11,000 --> 01:22:12,000
He got them.

1238
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:14,000
He actually got them involved.

1239
01:22:14,000 --> 01:22:18,000
He was, had been a teacher, you know, in Chicago.

1240
01:22:18,000 --> 01:22:23,000
And so then they arrayed all of this hardware in front of us.

1241
01:22:23,000 --> 01:22:26,000
That's what I was really scared.

1242
01:22:26,000 --> 01:22:28,000
Really, really scared.

1243
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:33,000
I was sitting on the steps holding onto this rail with both my hands like this.

1244
01:22:33,000 --> 01:22:38,000
And I remember thinking myself, this is probably it.

1245
01:22:38,000 --> 01:22:42,000
Because the idea was that we're going to wash us down the steps with the hoses

1246
01:22:42,000 --> 01:22:47,000
and then come and kill us with the sticks.

1247
01:22:47,000 --> 01:22:49,000
And I would have sat there.

1248
01:22:49,000 --> 01:22:51,000
I would have sat there.

1249
01:22:51,000 --> 01:22:55,000
And people have asked me, I mean, there was inconceivable to get up.

1250
01:22:55,000 --> 01:22:57,000
How could I get up?

1251
01:22:57,000 --> 01:22:58,000
How could I possibly?

1252
01:22:58,000 --> 01:23:02,000
Aside from the fact that I was the only white person in the group,

1253
01:23:02,000 --> 01:23:04,000
how could I possibly get up?

1254
01:23:04,000 --> 01:23:05,000
I mean, who had the option?

1255
01:23:05,000 --> 01:23:07,000
To get up, you don't have an option.

1256
01:23:07,000 --> 01:23:10,000
You know, you got there on your own two feet.

1257
01:23:10,000 --> 01:23:13,000
You're going to stay there with everybody.

1258
01:23:13,000 --> 01:23:16,000
And so that's when James Forman came up and he distracted the police chief

1259
01:23:16,000 --> 01:23:20,000
and behind his back, he went like this, this man, get up and get the hell out of there.

1260
01:23:20,000 --> 01:23:21,000
And we did.

1261
01:23:21,000 --> 01:23:22,000
We got up.

1262
01:23:22,000 --> 01:23:24,000
Very dignified and we left.

1263
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:27,000
So I consider that twice, he saved my life.

1264
01:23:27,000 --> 01:23:33,000
If he had been in any way in temperate or off the wall in Mississippi

1265
01:23:33,000 --> 01:23:38,000
when we would stop that night, who knows what would have happened.

1266
01:23:38,000 --> 01:23:42,000
And then in Danville, we knew what was going to happen.

1267
01:23:42,000 --> 01:23:49,000
But you see, he had the stature to know when it was time to retreat.

1268
01:23:49,000 --> 01:23:56,000
And he was not a crazy hothead because if he had been, he would have just said,

1269
01:23:56,000 --> 01:24:00,000
oh, okay, so we'll have four or five people killed out here today.

1270
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:02,000
And he didn't.

1271
01:24:02,000 --> 01:24:05,000
He wouldn't do that.

1272
01:24:05,000 --> 01:24:08,000
So I was incredibly fond of him.

1273
01:24:08,000 --> 01:24:11,000
I really just loved him.

1274
01:24:11,000 --> 01:24:14,000
And he was also brave in other ways, you know.

1275
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:20,000
Like, who is brave enough to buy 20 cars at once, you know.

1276
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:29,000
And just the idea of having the money, that was $2,000 a car, by the way, in those days.

1277
01:24:29,000 --> 01:24:34,000
So he said to himself, I could do this.

1278
01:24:34,000 --> 01:24:37,000
Who knows if we only had $40,000 in the bank.

1279
01:24:37,000 --> 01:24:39,000
We might have said now is the time.

1280
01:24:39,000 --> 01:24:40,000
He was brave.

1281
01:24:40,000 --> 01:24:43,000
He was brave in that way.

1282
01:24:43,000 --> 01:24:49,000
And then he put up with all sorts of unbelievable people, as we will know.

1283
01:24:49,000 --> 01:24:58,000
You know, I mean, really, the SNCC people as a group were definitely, what should I say, exceptional.

1284
01:24:58,000 --> 01:25:00,000
And all respect.

1285
01:25:00,000 --> 01:25:07,000
And he put up with a lot of divas, a lot of divas.

1286
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:10,000
So I had nothing but respect for him.

1287
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:12,000
Nothing.

1288
01:25:12,000 --> 01:25:16,000
And he's never been treated properly.

1289
01:25:16,000 --> 01:25:25,000
And to think that he was reduced to that person in the movie, in Selma, you know,

1290
01:25:25,000 --> 01:25:32,000
when it was totally bizarre, a totally bizarre portrayal of him.

1291
01:25:32,000 --> 01:25:34,000
You know, makes me feel bad.

1292
01:25:34,000 --> 01:25:39,000
It makes me feel bad to read a book just recently, that he was petulant, that he was jealous.

1293
01:25:39,000 --> 01:25:45,000
He was a book, no, no, no, no, no, wrong guy, wrong guy.

1294
01:25:45,000 --> 01:25:49,000
And again, he certainly was not flawless by any means.

1295
01:25:49,000 --> 01:25:53,000
And he could be, he definitely very brusque, very breath.

1296
01:25:53,000 --> 01:25:55,000
But he would look at you, he would tell you the truth.

1297
01:25:55,000 --> 01:25:57,000
He would tell you the truth.

1298
01:25:57,000 --> 01:25:59,000
Now you didn't do that right.

1299
01:25:59,000 --> 01:26:02,000
You know, no, you didn't do that right.

1300
01:26:02,000 --> 01:26:06,000
And I don't remember that he spared himself either.

1301
01:26:06,000 --> 01:26:11,000
So he, and then of course, what happened to him was very sad.

1302
01:26:11,000 --> 01:26:22,000
Now all the time that I knew him, I knew him really well up until 1967.

1303
01:26:22,000 --> 01:26:29,000
So I knew him well from 1961, the fall of 1961 to the spring of 1967.

1304
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:34,000
All that time, I did not know that he had had a psychiatric history.

1305
01:26:34,000 --> 01:26:40,000
I didn't know that he had had a breakdown as a young man.

1306
01:26:40,000 --> 01:26:52,000
There was absolutely nothing to indicate in any one of his dealings that he had ever had any problem.

1307
01:26:52,000 --> 01:26:58,000
I don't think I was certainly, you know, was not a nurse then or anything.

1308
01:26:58,000 --> 01:27:07,000
But I think I was, I was pretty sensitive to weird people, you know, like five minutes within five minutes.

1309
01:27:07,000 --> 01:27:08,000
He, he wasn't like that.

1310
01:27:08,000 --> 01:27:09,000
He was not like that.

1311
01:27:09,000 --> 01:27:13,000
He showed no sign of psychiatric problems whatsoever.

1312
01:27:13,000 --> 01:27:15,000
And then he, he crashed.

1313
01:27:15,000 --> 01:27:18,000
And then he had a breakdown.

1314
01:27:18,000 --> 01:27:26,000
And now whether, it's hard to believe that it was not a result of accumulated stress

1315
01:27:26,000 --> 01:27:37,000
and accumulated stroma, a trauma because he was in a very responsible period for many years.

1316
01:27:37,000 --> 01:27:45,000
And considering that he had had a previous breakdown, I suppose it's not surprising.

1317
01:27:45,000 --> 01:27:48,000
Now, Dinky Forman managed to get him back.

1318
01:27:48,000 --> 01:27:51,000
She took him to Puerto Rico.

1319
01:27:51,000 --> 01:27:56,000
And in that period, Elizabeth "Betita" Sutherland Martínez worked with him on his book.

1320
01:27:56,000 --> 01:27:58,000
He, he came back.

1321
01:27:58,000 --> 01:28:02,000
And I think he had altogether three breakdowns.

1322
01:28:02,000 --> 01:28:09,000
And his final breakdown, I remember somebody telling me who was a medical professional,

1323
01:28:09,000 --> 01:28:13,000
that with the final breakdown, he, he had two options then.

1324
01:28:13,000 --> 01:28:17,000
He was going to deconstruct completely.

1325
01:28:17,000 --> 01:28:29,000
And then he would be able to be rehabilitated through therapy and medication and restore his personality.

1326
01:28:29,000 --> 01:28:37,000
Or without intervention, he was going to level off at some chronic state.

1327
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:40,000
And he, at that point, refused treatment.

1328
01:28:40,000 --> 01:28:42,000
And that's exactly what happened.

1329
01:28:42,000 --> 01:28:48,000
Is he leveled off at a chronic state and became a totally different person.

1330
01:28:48,000 --> 01:29:02,000
And this is the person who was talking about class warfare, who became this, this lapdog of the Democratic point.

1331
01:29:03,000 --> 01:29:14,000
And I remember having a knockdown drag out fight with him about Ed Koch, the mayor, whom I load, and despised.

1332
01:29:14,000 --> 01:29:20,000
And he, he was giving some sort of a reason why it's important to support Ed Koch.

1333
01:29:20,000 --> 01:29:22,000
Oh my God.

1334
01:29:22,000 --> 01:29:29,000
And then we, we became very, we became distant.

1335
01:29:29,000 --> 01:29:35,000
You know, I mean, I cared about him. He'd come and visit me. He even stayed at my house once.

1336
01:29:35,000 --> 01:29:41,000
He, he, by that time, and when he was in his very sick period, he was convinced that he was being poisoned.

1337
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:46,000
He refused to eat anything with me. We'd go to a restaurant. He wouldn't eat.

1338
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:50,000
And I just said to him, if you're afraid that you're being poisoned, give me the food I'll eat at first.

1339
01:29:50,000 --> 01:29:53,000
And if nothing happens to me, then you can eat it.

1340
01:29:53,000 --> 01:29:57,000
I mean, I just treated it like, well, you okay? That's, this is what you think.

1341
01:29:57,000 --> 01:29:59,000
Let's try that.

1342
01:29:59,000 --> 01:30:04,000
And he ended up, well, everybody knows how he ended up. He ended up in Washington.

1343
01:30:04,000 --> 01:30:09,000
He was extremely bizarre, bizarre.

1344
01:30:09,000 --> 01:30:12,000
He was a great man.

1345
01:30:12,000 --> 01:30:20,000
He has not been treated like a great man in all these years of historiography.

1346
01:30:20,000 --> 01:30:32,000
And I am totally convinced we would have had a collection of extremely brilliant people who would have been all over the place if it hadn't been for him.

1347
01:30:32,000 --> 01:30:38,000
I mean, he really, he was, he invented the hub, the wheel and the hub.

1348
01:30:38,000 --> 01:30:42,000
And he was standing right there, right in the center of the hub.

1349
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:47,000
And I mean, he invented, you know, the campus travelers.

1350
01:30:47,000 --> 01:30:52,000
He invented, I said, the friends groups.

1351
01:30:52,000 --> 01:30:57,000
And it was all to serve the rural areas.

1352
01:30:57,000 --> 01:31:02,000
That was all, we didn't put it in those terms, but now looking back, that's what it was.

1353
01:31:02,000 --> 01:31:07,000
We were all serving the work.

1354
01:31:07,000 --> 01:31:12,000
And that's what his model was, because that's what he did in his life.

1355
01:31:12,000 --> 01:31:16,000
I don't believe, I mean, I think he took vacations.

1356
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:20,000
He certainly didn't, he didn't care about clothes.

1357
01:31:20,000 --> 01:31:22,000
There was nothing that he did.

1358
01:31:22,000 --> 01:31:26,000
He didn't care about food. He didn't care about any of that.

1359
01:31:26,000 --> 01:31:30,000
And he was very ruthless about publicity.

1360
01:31:30,000 --> 01:31:33,000
He wanted publicity for the work.

1361
01:31:33,000 --> 01:31:37,000
I don't remember anything where he would wanted publicity for himself.

1362
01:31:37,000 --> 01:31:40,000
He was not, he wasn't like that.

1363
01:31:40,000 --> 01:31:42,000
He wasn't.

1364
01:31:42,000 --> 01:31:45,000
Thank you for being the first on that.

1365
01:31:45,000 --> 01:31:48,000
She got him through twice.

1366
01:31:48,000 --> 01:31:50,000
Thank you, say who she was and this kind of thing.

1367
01:31:50,000 --> 01:31:57,000
Oh yes, well, she was his Constance "Dinky" Romilly, the mother of his two children.

1368
01:31:57,000 --> 01:32:01,000
Both of whom are accomplished.

1369
01:32:01,000 --> 01:32:05,000
James Forman Jr. is a professor at Yale.

1370
01:32:05,000 --> 01:32:14,000
And the younger son, Chaka, is an actor and a teacher in California.

1371
01:32:14,000 --> 01:32:19,000
So it was a long series of heart-wraening thing to watch.

1372
01:32:19,000 --> 01:32:26,000
And I remember Betty and I went to see him, a couple of months before he died.

1373
01:32:26,000 --> 01:32:32,000
And he was living in this sort of rehab home after surgery.

1374
01:32:33,000 --> 01:32:40,000
Then he had an obsession that Aretha Franklin.

1375
01:32:40,000 --> 01:32:45,000
And that's all he would talk about was Aretha Franklin and being a Native American.

1376
01:32:45,000 --> 01:32:48,000
And I looked at him and he said, and I'm a Native American too.

1377
01:32:48,000 --> 01:32:50,000
And I remember looking at him.

1378
01:32:50,000 --> 01:32:54,000
I said, really? And he showed a little flesh of his old self.

1379
01:32:54,000 --> 01:32:57,000
He said, yeah, I'm telling you.

1380
01:32:57,000 --> 01:32:59,000
Yeah, yeah, I'm telling you.

1381
01:32:59,000 --> 01:33:02,000
And but that disappeared.

1382
01:33:02,000 --> 01:33:07,000
And then we had a big party for him, you know, when he was 75.

1383
01:33:07,000 --> 01:33:10,000
But that was before he had stabilized at that point.

1384
01:33:10,000 --> 01:33:19,000
He was like, he was like, your chronic eccentric person.

1385
01:33:19,000 --> 01:33:22,000
He didn't have big ups, he didn't have big downs.

1386
01:33:22,000 --> 01:33:27,000
But he stabilized at a level that was a different person.

1387
01:33:27,000 --> 01:33:32,000
And then I don't know the technical name for that.

1388
01:33:32,000 --> 01:33:36,000
But, you know, his politics were different.

1389
01:33:36,000 --> 01:33:43,000
He didn't have any great passion left, you know, he had spent it all.

1390
01:33:43,000 --> 01:33:47,000
He gave himself to us.

1391
01:33:47,000 --> 01:33:53,000
Unfortunately, there are a lot of people who don't realize what a gift that was.

1392
01:33:54,000 --> 01:33:56,000
So.

1393
01:33:56,000 --> 01:34:00,000
And for people who don't know, it's just really the person who

1394
01:34:00,000 --> 01:34:07,000
is a secretary of SNCC and the infrastructure

1395
01:34:07,000 --> 01:34:10,000
to support people working in the field.

1396
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:16,000
And he felt that position until sometimes 65.

1397
01:34:16,000 --> 01:34:22,000
But he was still very much in the leadership.

1398
01:34:22,000 --> 01:34:25,000
And, yeah.

1399
01:34:25,000 --> 01:34:30,000
And then Ruby Doris came in there.

1400
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:34,000
Well, all I remember, I remember Pete Seeger was there.

1401
01:34:34,000 --> 01:34:39,000
Pete Seeger was in Greenwood in 1963.

1402
01:34:39,000 --> 01:34:45,000
I think I remember Bob and I was supposed to take Pete Seeger around.

1403
01:34:46,000 --> 01:34:51,000
And Bob Dylan was at the festival.

1404
01:34:51,000 --> 01:34:59,000
Danny Lyon did several photographs of him singing there.

1405
01:34:59,000 --> 01:35:02,000
And it was out in a big field.

1406
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:05,000
And he sang songs that were fabulous.

1407
01:35:05,000 --> 01:35:11,000
And it totally incomprehensible seemed to me to the audience.

1408
01:35:11,000 --> 01:35:17,000
He was singing, I remember, he sang a song that I totally love and agreed everywhere.

1409
01:35:17,000 --> 01:35:24,000
Which was With God on Our Side", With God on Our Side", to a group of people

1410
01:35:24,000 --> 01:35:27,000
who was religious faith meant everything to them.

1411
01:35:27,000 --> 01:35:32,000
And who got it held them together for 300 years.

1412
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:35,000
And here he was singing With God on Our Side".

1413
01:35:35,000 --> 01:35:38,000
I mean, I don't know what people got at him.

1414
01:35:38,000 --> 01:35:42,000
I don't know what they made of him.

1415
01:35:42,000 --> 01:35:47,000
I think that's where I might have met the Green family first.

1416
01:35:47,000 --> 01:35:49,000
I don't remember how long we stayed there.

1417
01:35:49,000 --> 01:35:52,000
I mean, we were only there a few days, only a few days.

1418
01:35:52,000 --> 01:35:56,000
But enough to, of course, to get in the trouble possible even with a cup.

1419
01:35:56,000 --> 01:36:00,000
I think you have to shoot for 8 and then the more girls out,

1420
01:36:00,000 --> 01:36:03,000
or like, from the safe courts, or even...

1421
01:36:08,000 --> 01:36:17,000
I'm trying to think I had only been in the rural south, in the white side, in Alabama,

1422
01:36:17,000 --> 01:36:20,000
through Bob's family. I had not been in the black side.

1423
01:36:20,000 --> 01:36:23,000
Was this before or after Dandel?

1424
01:36:23,000 --> 01:36:25,000
Well, that's what I'm trying to remember.

1425
01:36:25,000 --> 01:36:27,000
It seems to me it was after Danville.

1426
01:36:27,000 --> 01:36:29,000
I think Danville was June.

1427
01:36:29,000 --> 01:36:33,000
We got married in August, so it must have been somewhere around July.

1428
01:36:33,000 --> 01:36:37,000
What a time to have a festival in July in Mississippi.

1429
01:36:37,000 --> 01:36:40,000
Greenwood.

1430
01:36:40,000 --> 01:36:43,000
Or was it that summer of 1963?

1431
01:36:43,000 --> 01:36:44,000
Am I right?

1432
01:36:44,000 --> 01:36:46,000
It was a tree, but I'm not sure why I'm in 60.

1433
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:47,000
Yeah.

1434
01:36:47,000 --> 01:36:51,000
We can find that.

1435
01:36:51,000 --> 01:36:58,000
Well, I don't remember making a distinction between rural Mississippi and urban Mississippi.

1436
01:36:58,000 --> 01:37:02,000
I remember the Welcome to the Magnolia State"'s line.

1437
01:37:02,000 --> 01:37:07,000
You saw that sign. Your heart went to your feet and didn't matter where you were going.

1438
01:37:07,000 --> 01:37:11,000
I think I only ended up being in Jackson maybe twice.

1439
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:13,000
That was the only urban area.

1440
01:37:13,000 --> 01:37:18,000
I didn't consider where we were in Greenwood to be urban quite.

1441
01:37:18,000 --> 01:37:27,000
To me, the whole place was like a nightmare, a living nightmare.

1442
01:37:27,000 --> 01:37:30,000
That whole summer was a nightmare.

1443
01:37:30,000 --> 01:37:31,000
Definitely.

1444
01:37:31,000 --> 01:37:32,000
A nightmare.

1445
01:37:32,000 --> 01:37:35,000
I'm going to back to what you said about summer, 1964.

1446
01:37:35,000 --> 01:37:38,000
I'm going to back back a little.

1447
01:37:38,000 --> 01:37:42,000
Last time when you were talking about your chronology,

1448
01:37:42,000 --> 01:37:46,000
you were working for the Southern Regional Council in volunteering with me.

1449
01:37:46,000 --> 01:37:47,000
That's right.

1450
01:37:47,000 --> 01:37:51,000
At a certain point, you moved from the SRC to the SNCC.

1451
01:37:51,000 --> 01:37:56,000
What was it like to work at the Wandersteads the other day?

1452
01:37:56,000 --> 01:38:05,000
Well, the SRC was just a regular office situation.

1453
01:38:05,000 --> 01:38:10,000
Jane and I both were well played clerical workers.

1454
01:38:10,000 --> 01:38:13,000
She already at least had a part of a master's.

1455
01:38:13,000 --> 01:38:15,000
I was a college graduate.

1456
01:38:15,000 --> 01:38:17,000
I think we were doing paper pushing.

1457
01:38:17,000 --> 01:38:19,000
I don't know exactly what we were doing.

1458
01:38:19,000 --> 01:38:24,000
I mean, I was still ostensibly keeping track of the sit-in movement

1459
01:38:24,000 --> 01:38:26,000
and statistics and all of that.

1460
01:38:26,000 --> 01:38:31,000
Now, we're back to this winter of 6162.

1461
01:38:31,000 --> 01:38:43,000
At some point, the FBI came and questioned the Leslie Dunbar who was the head of SRC then questioned him about me.

1462
01:38:43,000 --> 01:38:45,000
He told me.

1463
01:38:45,000 --> 01:38:48,000
This is what he told me.

1464
01:38:48,000 --> 01:38:54,000
They apparently came with a photo of me somewhere.

1465
01:38:54,000 --> 01:38:57,000
I mean, I never saw the photo.

1466
01:38:57,000 --> 01:39:07,000
I don't know if I ever asked a list on board about it, but I always had some hopes for a photo.

1467
01:39:07,000 --> 01:39:10,000
But what that photo could have been.

1468
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:11,000
I hoped.

1469
01:39:11,000 --> 01:39:17,000
I hoped that it was of me at a poor ropes and concerts.

1470
01:39:17,000 --> 01:39:22,000
That's what I hoped that they had a photo of me anyway.

1471
01:39:22,000 --> 01:39:26,000
So he fired me.

1472
01:39:26,000 --> 01:39:29,000
Now, I had been talking to James Forman about.

1473
01:39:29,000 --> 01:39:31,000
James Forman had asked me to come on the staff.

1474
01:39:31,000 --> 01:39:34,000
But there was no money at the time.

1475
01:39:34,000 --> 01:39:41,000
And I said, well, I might as well stay here and get my salary paid, you know, and I'll come and work at night.

1476
01:39:41,000 --> 01:39:43,000
So that's what I did.

1477
01:39:43,000 --> 01:39:48,000
And of course, my life ended up being in the evenings.

1478
01:39:48,000 --> 01:39:49,000
It's not.

1479
01:39:49,000 --> 01:39:51,000
But I still had, you know, friends.

1480
01:39:51,000 --> 01:39:54,000
And Jane was still at S.R.C.

1481
01:39:54,000 --> 01:39:56,000
And we lived together.

1482
01:39:56,000 --> 01:39:59,000
So it was all kind of tidy, tidy thing.

1483
01:39:59,000 --> 01:40:03,000
Then the FBI came and then he claimed.

1484
01:40:03,000 --> 01:40:05,000
Now, this was all from him.

1485
01:40:05,000 --> 01:40:12,000
He claimed that they had come and that two or three months later he had decided that I was now redundant.

1486
01:40:12,000 --> 01:40:16,000
And that there was no point in paying me a salary to clip articles.

1487
01:40:16,000 --> 01:40:18,000
They could get anyone to clip articles.

1488
01:40:18,000 --> 01:40:20,000
So they could get a service, a clipping service.

1489
01:40:20,000 --> 01:40:22,000
That's what they had in those days.

1490
01:40:22,000 --> 01:40:24,000
Is a clipping service.

1491
01:40:24,000 --> 01:40:27,000
So he called me in and he fired me.

1492
01:40:27,000 --> 01:40:30,000
So I went to James Forman.

1493
01:40:30,000 --> 01:40:33,000
I said, okay, now's your chance.

1494
01:40:33,000 --> 01:40:35,000
You can put me on the staff.

1495
01:40:35,000 --> 01:40:37,000
So he said, okay.

1496
01:40:37,000 --> 01:40:40,000
I think he had started asking me around the winter.

1497
01:40:40,000 --> 01:40:46,000
And if I had been him as administrator, I definitely would have hired me.

1498
01:40:46,000 --> 01:40:50,000
You know, because they were, first of all, I did anything.

1499
01:40:50,000 --> 01:40:53,000
Put me at the memory graph machine for four hours.

1500
01:40:53,000 --> 01:40:56,000
I do it.

1501
01:40:56,000 --> 01:41:01,000
I was just so thrilled to be there, whatever I could do.

1502
01:41:01,000 --> 01:41:07,000
And I was, by then, you know, I was skilled in, I could put out a newsletter.

1503
01:41:07,000 --> 01:41:09,000
And I could write letters.

1504
01:41:09,000 --> 01:41:11,000
And I could write affidavits.

1505
01:41:11,000 --> 01:41:15,000
And I could do all of this stuff.

1506
01:41:15,000 --> 01:41:20,000
Many years later, in fact, I think it might have been at his memorial.

1507
01:41:20,000 --> 01:41:22,000
I'm not positive.

1508
01:41:22,000 --> 01:41:25,000
But Leslie Dunbar showed up.

1509
01:41:25,000 --> 01:41:29,000
And I took a lot of, this you might want to get.

1510
01:41:29,000 --> 01:41:32,000
Well, I'm going to, I'll tell the story.

1511
01:41:32,000 --> 01:41:34,000
I'll tell the story.

1512
01:41:35,000 --> 01:41:42,000
I did take some immoderate pleasure in introducing my daughter, Margaret, to Leslie Dunbar.

1513
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:49,000
And saying, this is the man who fired me when the FBI came.

1514
01:41:49,000 --> 01:41:54,000
Now, he claimed that I was redundant and that the FBI had nothing to do with that.

1515
01:41:54,000 --> 01:42:01,000
And you could possibly give him some credence in that, because he didn't fire me the next day.

1516
01:42:01,000 --> 01:42:03,000
He fired me two or three months later.

1517
01:42:03,000 --> 01:42:07,000
And he didn't tell me that they had been there until he fired me.

1518
01:42:07,000 --> 01:42:12,000
So you could possibly say that on the other hand, on the other hand.

1519
01:42:12,000 --> 01:42:15,000
On the other hand.

1520
01:42:15,000 --> 01:42:19,000
I'll just say that.

1521
01:42:19,000 --> 01:42:22,000
And I did this as many years later.

1522
01:42:22,000 --> 01:42:25,000
He also fired Jeff Minnes.

1523
01:42:25,000 --> 01:42:26,000
Did he?

1524
01:42:26,000 --> 01:42:31,000
Yeah, he also then came over to SNCC, and they're being fired by the SRC.

1525
01:42:31,000 --> 01:42:36,000
So SNCC got some really good details fired by the SRC.

1526
01:42:36,000 --> 01:42:42,000
Oh my God, we don't have time to even go into some of these characters like Jack and people like that.

1527
01:42:42,000 --> 01:42:55,000
Well, you said that Jane Bond said that I was fired because I participated in a demonstration about the Cuban Missile Crisis that was organized by Howard Zinn.

1528
01:42:55,000 --> 01:43:00,000
And I said maybe that's the photo that the FBI had.

1529
01:43:00,000 --> 01:43:01,000
Now they did have my name.

1530
01:43:01,000 --> 01:43:07,000
I know that because I think Howard told me that they, I think there were 23 of us.

1531
01:43:07,000 --> 01:43:09,000
They knew every single person's name.

1532
01:43:09,000 --> 01:43:11,000
Howard Zinn told me.

1533
01:43:11,000 --> 01:43:13,000
So that's possible.

1534
01:43:13,000 --> 01:43:16,000
I don't know what the photo was.

1535
01:43:16,000 --> 01:43:20,000
And I mean, I said to give him credit.

1536
01:43:20,000 --> 01:43:27,000
But maybe on the other hand, if I had an employee that the FBI came about, I wouldn't wait three months.

1537
01:43:27,000 --> 01:43:31,000
You know, I would discuss it with them right away.

1538
01:43:31,000 --> 01:43:34,000
So there's something off there.

1539
01:43:34,000 --> 01:43:41,000
So when you started working with SNCC full time, there are a couple of things that you were working on.

1540
01:43:41,000 --> 01:43:45,000
One was the Civil Liberties Conference for a workshop.

1541
01:43:45,000 --> 01:43:50,000
And then you were also working with Julian Bond on communication.

1542
01:43:50,000 --> 01:43:56,000
Can you talk about those at work?

1543
01:43:56,000 --> 01:43:58,000
Okay, so this is going to be hard.

1544
01:43:58,000 --> 01:44:02,000
I have to talk about Julian now.

1545
01:44:02,000 --> 01:44:03,000
Well, let's see.

1546
01:44:03,000 --> 01:44:09,000
I started working with Julian, the winter of 61-62.

1547
01:44:09,000 --> 01:44:16,000
And right away, we meshed.

1548
01:44:16,000 --> 01:44:20,000
And probably you couldn't get two more different people.

1549
01:44:20,000 --> 01:44:26,000
Because, you know, I was, I'm sure I was hard to deal with.

1550
01:44:26,000 --> 01:44:29,000
I think I was hard to deal with by some of the people there.

1551
01:44:29,000 --> 01:44:35,000
Because, you know, when I said I'm going to be somewhere at nine o'clock, I was there at nine o'clock.

1552
01:44:35,000 --> 01:44:38,000
And that was the hardest thing to meet.

1553
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:43,000
It was just to, you know, we'd say, oh, we're going to meet at nine o'clock on Thursday.

1554
01:44:43,000 --> 01:44:47,000
And it might be nine p.m. on Tuesday.

1555
01:44:47,000 --> 01:44:50,000
I found that very hard to deal with.

1556
01:44:50,000 --> 01:44:55,000
Now, I don't know if I interpreted it as a southern way of life.

1557
01:44:55,000 --> 01:45:00,000
But it might have been anything but a frenzy New York way of life.

1558
01:45:00,000 --> 01:45:04,000
That's, I'm willing to grant that.

1559
01:45:04,000 --> 01:45:06,000
So we had different ways.

1560
01:45:06,000 --> 01:45:10,000
I mean, I was, you know, really hard driven.

1561
01:45:10,000 --> 01:45:18,000
And he was much more relaxed, relaxed, meaning coming in later, breathing earlier, and coming back.

1562
01:45:18,000 --> 01:45:24,000
But we really got along well, extremely well.

1563
01:45:24,000 --> 01:45:34,000
And he was well known to love gossip.

1564
01:45:34,000 --> 01:45:36,000
He loved gossip.

1565
01:45:36,000 --> 01:45:39,000
He loved funny stories about people.

1566
01:45:39,000 --> 01:45:45,000
The interesting thing is that when I needed a confidant about personal matters,

1567
01:45:45,000 --> 01:45:52,000
which I will not go into, who did I pick but you want to talk to?

1568
01:45:52,000 --> 01:45:56,000
And that was early on.

1569
01:45:56,000 --> 01:45:59,000
And I'm thinking, I've been thinking since he died.

1570
01:45:59,000 --> 01:46:01,000
Why I did that.

1571
01:46:01,000 --> 01:46:03,000
There was something about him.

1572
01:46:03,000 --> 01:46:05,000
I trusted him.

1573
01:46:05,000 --> 01:46:16,000
I don't believe that whatever I told him, and I know what I told him, that he ever, ever, ever mentioned that, to another living soul.

1574
01:46:16,000 --> 01:46:20,000
So there was a lot of respect there.

1575
01:46:20,000 --> 01:46:24,000
And of course, he happened to be one of the funniest people who ever lived.

1576
01:46:24,000 --> 01:46:27,000
And I'm very fortunate.

1577
01:46:27,000 --> 01:46:31,000
I just had lunch with Pamela Sue Horowitz, last Saturday.

1578
01:46:31,000 --> 01:46:35,000
And I'm very fortunate that I have a lot of his emails.

1579
01:46:35,000 --> 01:46:40,000
I don't think I ever destroyed one email that he ever wrote to me.

1580
01:46:40,000 --> 01:46:48,000
So someday I have to get them all together and print them out and give them to her.

1581
01:46:48,000 --> 01:46:54,000
So he was also really unique.

1582
01:46:54,000 --> 01:47:03,000
One time, I think it was probably around 1963, I said to him, Julian, let's write a book.

1583
01:47:03,000 --> 01:47:12,000
And of course, the two of us, you know, we were so far from writing a book as being able to fly to the moment.

1584
01:47:12,000 --> 01:47:20,000
Because one thing you needed was to have all of the pieces of paper together, you know, in one spot, filed and kept.

1585
01:47:20,000 --> 01:47:23,000
You didn't have to.

1586
01:47:23,000 --> 01:47:28,000
And I'm thinking if we had written a book, wouldn't that have been great?

1587
01:47:28,000 --> 01:47:32,000
1963, 1963.

1588
01:47:32,000 --> 01:47:35,000
So I just, I loved working with him.

1589
01:47:35,000 --> 01:47:43,000
He also, he I'm not going to give you the actual incident.

1590
01:47:43,000 --> 01:48:02,000
But one thing that was very meaningful to me was that he defended me inside SNCC because I was being criticized for being the kind of person who got there at nine o'clock and was irritated when other people didn't get there at nine o'clock.

1591
01:48:02,000 --> 01:48:09,000
And he and Julian did not like conflict. He was very conflict diverse.

1592
01:48:09,000 --> 01:48:15,000
So when he took up for me in a staff meeting, that was very meaningful to me.

1593
01:48:15,000 --> 01:48:19,000
I never forgot that.

1594
01:48:19,000 --> 01:48:26,000
So I am finding it hard to realize that he's gone.

1595
01:48:26,000 --> 01:48:36,000
And it's not that I saw him so much. Maybe I saw him every year, but just knowing that he was there was was something meaningful to me.

1596
01:48:36,000 --> 01:48:44,000
And when I got that email that he had died and I somebody sent it to me was totally I think it was Dorothy Burlage.

1597
01:48:44,000 --> 01:48:50,000
She had seen it on the associated press. She was up like a four o'clock in the morning or something.

1598
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:56,000
When I woke up in the morning I saw it and I just couldn't. I said no no Julian.

1599
01:48:56,000 --> 01:49:04,000
So they were both totally different characters, completely different characters.

1600
01:49:04,000 --> 01:49:11,000
I was lucky to work with them. Really lucky.

1601
01:49:11,000 --> 01:49:18,000
We didn't have too many moments of a high danger. You know like I did with Jim.

1602
01:49:18,000 --> 01:49:24,000
Julian was cautious. He didn't put himself in too many moments of high danger.

1603
01:49:24,000 --> 01:49:34,000
Although he didn't travel to Mississippi quite a bit so there must have been some high danger there.

1604
01:49:34,000 --> 01:49:37,000
So that's what I would say.

1605
01:49:37,000 --> 01:49:43,000
How did you put out this feeling of hope and how to do it with the borders?

1606
01:49:43,000 --> 01:49:51,000
Well I think I've been trying to remember I remember laying out dummies of the student voice.

1607
01:49:51,000 --> 01:50:03,000
But I think Julian brought it to the guy who put out the black newspaper whose name I don't remember.

1608
01:50:03,000 --> 01:50:08,000
It might have been yes somebody at the Atlanta Inquirer. We did not put it.

1609
01:50:08,000 --> 01:50:13,000
We didn't do the type ourselves. We didn't set the type.

1610
01:50:13,000 --> 01:50:18,000
We didn't have the ability to make the photos.

1611
01:50:18,000 --> 01:50:22,000
But I remember doing many dummies.

1612
01:50:22,000 --> 01:50:26,000
Yes we wrote all the stories.

1613
01:50:26,000 --> 01:50:37,000
Later on we also tried to teach staff people and the summer volunteers both about how to deal with the press.

1614
01:50:37,000 --> 01:50:49,000
He and I really saw how to deal with the press because there were some press people that we really liked a lot.

1615
01:50:49,000 --> 01:50:56,000
Even if we didn't like them we always told them the truth.

1616
01:50:56,000 --> 01:51:03,000
That's something that we taught the volunteers.

1617
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:07,000
And since then I've always taught people.

1618
01:51:07,000 --> 01:51:12,000
If you have a demonstration don't say there were 500 people when there were 42 people.

1619
01:51:12,000 --> 01:51:20,000
Say there were 42 people because the guy who covers it the next time he's not going to come if he knows.

1620
01:51:20,000 --> 01:51:23,000
Now nobody taught us that in journalism school.

1621
01:51:23,000 --> 01:51:27,000
Actually neither of us ever went to journalism school but I did run the newspaper.

1622
01:51:27,000 --> 01:51:30,000
I think he was on the newspaper if I'm not mistaken.

1623
01:51:30,000 --> 01:51:34,000
With the newspaper at the Morehouse.

1624
01:51:34,000 --> 01:51:37,000
I'm not sure.

1625
01:51:37,000 --> 01:51:41,000
When he left the house he worked with Atlanta and choir.

1626
01:51:41,000 --> 01:51:45,000
We are.

1627
01:51:45,000 --> 01:51:49,000
So we liked these guys and they trusted us.

1628
01:51:49,000 --> 01:51:56,000
We had really looking back at a unique and wonderful relationship with them.

1629
01:51:56,000 --> 01:51:59,000
A lot of them gravitated towards him.

1630
01:51:59,000 --> 01:52:04,000
He was very beautiful and very charismatic.

1631
01:52:04,000 --> 01:52:07,000
I was this New York girl.

1632
01:52:07,000 --> 01:52:10,000
They weren't going to be dwelling over me.

1633
01:52:10,000 --> 01:52:15,000
Although Fred Powledge which became quite fun at the end.

1634
01:52:15,000 --> 01:52:17,000
But he was very charismatic.

1635
01:52:17,000 --> 01:52:20,000
He was great to be around.

1636
01:52:20,000 --> 01:52:27,000
We did these live foam conversations while they were live but then they taped them.

1637
01:52:27,000 --> 01:52:32,000
And even then he was a master at that ten times.

1638
01:52:32,000 --> 01:52:36,000
Well somebody would interview us over the phone.

1639
01:52:36,000 --> 01:52:38,000
I was good.

1640
01:52:38,000 --> 01:52:40,000
I was earnest in everything.

1641
01:52:40,000 --> 01:52:42,000
He was witty and funny.

1642
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:45,000
I mean he had to be one of the funniest people who ever lived.

1643
01:52:45,000 --> 01:52:50,000
And he could just knuckle up these widestisms like it was nothing.

1644
01:52:50,000 --> 01:52:53,000
You know the younger he was the quicker he was.

1645
01:52:53,000 --> 01:52:58,000
You know so when he got most people saw him when he already was down half his speed.

1646
01:52:58,000 --> 01:53:02,000
You can imagine what he actually was when he was twenty-two.

1647
01:53:02,000 --> 01:53:05,000
And we were born on the same date.

1648
01:53:05,000 --> 01:53:07,000
I mean the same day.

1649
01:53:07,000 --> 01:53:09,000
Not the same year.

1650
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:12,000
I'm two years older.

1651
01:53:12,000 --> 01:53:16,000
So they knew if they talked to Julian they would get a good quote.

1652
01:53:16,000 --> 01:53:18,000
So they would always get a good quote.

1653
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:22,000
Then they would get the truth from us and they would get what actually happened.

1654
01:53:22,000 --> 01:53:27,000
And if we didn't know what happened we'd say we don't know what happened.

1655
01:53:27,000 --> 01:53:31,000
These are all things that have flown by the way inside.

1656
01:53:31,000 --> 01:53:38,000
You know so they were reasonably sure they didn't have to go double checking and triple checking and so on.

1657
01:53:38,000 --> 01:53:43,000
And then we called them constantly and we sent press release, press release, press release.

1658
01:53:43,000 --> 01:53:45,000
Now we had...

1659
01:53:45,000 --> 01:53:50,000
If I got this correct, I'm not sure I do.

1660
01:53:50,000 --> 01:53:54,000
We identified black people.

1661
01:53:54,000 --> 01:53:55,000
Deliberately.

1662
01:53:55,000 --> 01:53:59,000
Of course we didn't say black then we said negro.

1663
01:53:59,000 --> 01:54:02,000
Now it looks a little strange.

1664
01:54:02,000 --> 01:54:10,000
But we did it deliberately because we wanted people to know that they were black people in the front of this.

1665
01:54:10,000 --> 01:54:14,000
So when people got arrested it was especially important.

1666
01:54:14,000 --> 01:54:21,000
Now I'm not sure that really came through to a lot of people wondering because we didn't say white.

1667
01:54:21,000 --> 01:54:24,000
White was the default.

1668
01:54:24,000 --> 01:54:28,000
But we wanted people to know that they were black people in the leadership.

1669
01:54:28,000 --> 01:54:34,000
I hope some historian will write that down somewhere because it will definitely look strange in 20 or 30 years.

1670
01:54:34,000 --> 01:54:45,000
Why an organization that was black led kept making a whole point only about the race of the person when it was a black person.

1671
01:54:45,000 --> 01:54:48,000
But there was a reason for that.

1672
01:54:48,000 --> 01:54:51,000
And we did that always, always.

1673
01:54:51,000 --> 01:54:53,000
I want to get ahead a little bit.

1674
01:54:53,000 --> 01:54:59,000
But so I know that you worked in the Atlanta office through the summer of 1963.

1675
01:54:59,000 --> 01:55:04,000
You involved Zeller and Mary in August?

1676
01:55:04,000 --> 01:55:07,000
Yes, we were married in August.

1677
01:55:07,000 --> 01:55:12,000
But to say through the summer is not quite right because part of that was in Dandel.

1678
01:55:12,000 --> 01:55:20,000
And then if we got the date right another part of it was in Greenwood at the film at the music festival.

1679
01:55:20,000 --> 01:55:27,000
So I wasn't based out of absolutely yes and got married in Atlanta.

1680
01:55:27,000 --> 01:55:31,000
And then you were about to go to Boston?

1681
01:55:31,000 --> 01:55:32,000
Yes.

1682
01:55:32,000 --> 01:55:36,000
And he's in graduate school and he's created a Boston Prince of SNCC?

1683
01:55:36,000 --> 01:55:37,000
No.

1684
01:55:37,000 --> 01:55:43,000
There was a Boston Prince of SNCC, and I created a Northeast regional office of Snick.

1685
01:55:43,000 --> 01:55:49,000
And I always made it, nobody paid the slightest bit of attention but I always made a big thing about that.

1686
01:55:49,000 --> 01:55:53,000
Because I was not, this was not a Friends of SNCC group.

1687
01:55:53,000 --> 01:55:57,000
I was a staff member and I took leadership directly from Atlanta.

1688
01:55:57,000 --> 01:56:00,000
And I was a staff member.

1689
01:56:00,000 --> 01:56:05,000
And most of the friends of SNCC not have a staff member.

1690
01:56:05,000 --> 01:56:07,000
That's right. Many of them had volunteers.

1691
01:56:07,000 --> 01:56:09,000
Some of them only had volunteers.

1692
01:56:09,000 --> 01:56:11,000
Thanks very much Chicago and New York.

1693
01:56:11,000 --> 01:56:16,000
I think she's a close to Friends of SNCC?

1694
01:56:16,000 --> 01:56:18,000
Well, it's sort of mixed.

1695
01:56:18,000 --> 01:56:19,000
I don't know.

1696
01:56:19,000 --> 01:56:21,000
You'd have to ask people who worked there.

1697
01:56:21,000 --> 01:56:24,000
But there were staff members there too.

1698
01:56:24,000 --> 01:56:26,000
I guess that was where I was.

1699
01:56:26,000 --> 01:56:27,000
Yeah.

1700
01:56:27,000 --> 01:56:35,000
And so you're in Boston and I know one of the things that you do is interview people who were going to be volunteers in the summer project

1701
01:56:35,000 --> 01:56:40,000
and decide where they should accept the applications.

1702
01:56:40,000 --> 01:56:43,000
Then you went to Greenwood that summer,

1703
01:56:43,000 --> 01:56:48,000
but 64 as part of the National Office in Greenwood.

1704
01:56:48,000 --> 01:56:52,000
And at some point you were in New York.

1705
01:56:52,000 --> 01:56:53,000
No.

1706
01:56:53,000 --> 01:56:55,000
You were about.

1707
01:56:55,000 --> 01:56:59,000
We went back to Cambridge where we were living.

1708
01:56:59,000 --> 01:57:03,000
He went back to school in 64, 65.

1709
01:57:03,000 --> 01:57:06,000
I ran the SNCC office, continued to run the SNCC office there.

1710
01:57:06,000 --> 01:57:08,000
I mean, the Northeast Regional,

1711
01:57:08,000 --> 01:57:11,000
the Friends of SNCC, whatever you want to call it in Boston,

1712
01:57:11,000 --> 01:57:13,000
and got pregnant.

1713
01:57:13,000 --> 01:57:20,000
And then I resigned from that particular work,

1714
01:57:20,000 --> 01:57:26,000
but not from the SNCC staff in the spring of 65.

1715
01:57:26,000 --> 01:57:29,000
Then my daughter was born.

1716
01:57:30,000 --> 01:57:37,000
We went back to Atlanta in the fall of 65.

1717
01:57:37,000 --> 01:57:40,000
And then we took a year's leave of absence.

1718
01:57:40,000 --> 01:57:47,000
And Bob was the campaign manager for the first anti-Vietnam War candidate in the country,

1719
01:57:47,000 --> 01:57:53,000
whose name was Robert Cook.

1720
01:57:53,000 --> 01:57:55,000
Thanks for your name.

1721
01:57:55,000 --> 01:57:57,000
We were in New Haven.

1722
01:57:58,000 --> 01:58:02,000
But one or the other of us always went to staff meetings.

1723
01:58:02,000 --> 01:58:07,000
So we were on leave, but we were still going to staff meetings.

1724
01:58:07,000 --> 01:58:10,000
We were still involved in staff discussions.

1725
01:58:10,000 --> 01:58:15,000
Can I ask, so when you said that you resigned from running the North?

1726
01:58:15,000 --> 01:58:18,000
You know, but you continued to work.

1727
01:58:18,000 --> 01:58:24,000
Oh, I don't remember if I did any work when we were still there.

1728
01:58:24,000 --> 01:58:29,000
When we came back to Atlanta, I brought the baby to work.

1729
01:58:29,000 --> 01:58:33,000
And then when I came back, that was the winter of 65.

1730
01:58:33,000 --> 01:58:37,000
If I'm not mistaken, the spring of winter 65, 66,

1731
01:58:37,000 --> 01:58:45,000
that's when Stokely [Carmichael] asked me to work on The (Black) Panther.

1732
01:58:45,000 --> 01:58:48,000
Now, while we were on leave, as I say,

1733
01:58:48,000 --> 01:58:52,000
Bob always went to staff meetings, and I did too if I was able.

1734
01:58:52,000 --> 01:59:00,000
But you know, at the time in 65, it was the custom you didn't work after your seventh month.

1735
01:59:00,000 --> 01:59:03,000
Now you work right up until the minute you give birth.

1736
01:59:03,000 --> 01:59:05,000
And was that when you resigned?

1737
01:59:05,000 --> 01:59:06,000
Yes.

1738
01:59:06,000 --> 01:59:08,000
But I didn't resign from SNCC.

1739
01:59:08,000 --> 01:59:10,000
I just stepped down from the office.

1740
01:59:10,000 --> 01:59:13,000
Bob took over running the office.

1741
01:59:13,000 --> 01:59:15,000
But he was in school for the first few years.

1742
01:59:15,000 --> 01:59:19,000
Yeah, but he was already, he was pretty, and never graduated.

1743
01:59:19,000 --> 01:59:21,000
I'm never finished.

1744
01:59:21,000 --> 01:59:24,000
And so she was born in July.

1745
01:59:24,000 --> 01:59:30,000
I probably, it was like late May, he had already finished his semester.

1746
01:59:30,000 --> 01:59:33,000
And he started running the SNCC office.

1747
01:59:33,000 --> 01:59:36,000
And...

1748
01:59:38,000 --> 01:59:42,000
So she's born in July.

1749
01:59:42,000 --> 01:59:44,000
She's born in July.

1750
01:59:44,000 --> 01:59:45,000
Yeah.

1751
01:59:45,000 --> 01:59:49,000
And that fall, you're back in Atlanta.

1752
01:59:49,000 --> 01:59:51,000
That's right.

1753
01:59:51,000 --> 01:59:55,000
At what point did you take the leave of absence?

1754
01:59:55,000 --> 01:59:59,000
It was probably...

1755
01:59:59,000 --> 02:00:03,000
shortly thereafter, maybe the winter.

1756
02:00:03,000 --> 02:00:13,000
And then we worked through the election, which was, again, November, I guess, of 66.

1757
02:00:13,000 --> 02:00:16,000
66.

1758
02:00:16,000 --> 02:00:19,000
And then we stayed there a few months, a couple of months after that.

1759
02:00:19,000 --> 02:00:25,000
Then we went south, and we were getting ready to go back to work with SNCC.

1760
02:00:25,000 --> 02:00:28,000
Because by that time...

1761
02:00:28,000 --> 02:00:33,000
Were you at the student meeting in December 66?

1762
02:00:33,000 --> 02:00:35,000
Bob was there.

1763
02:00:35,000 --> 02:00:38,000
But I wasn't there.

1764
02:00:38,000 --> 02:00:41,000
Can you tell us what he said about that meeting?

1765
02:00:41,000 --> 02:00:48,000
Oh, well, he said, you know, that white people were still here.

1766
02:00:48,000 --> 02:00:56,000
And the only thing I remember was that most of the white people there had abstained.

1767
02:00:56,000 --> 02:01:02,000
And that he, as I remember, I don't know if the Library of Congress is interviewing him,

1768
02:01:02,000 --> 02:01:05,000
but he apparently abstained.

1769
02:01:05,000 --> 02:01:11,000
I should say that the most coherent recounting of that meeting,

1770
02:01:11,000 --> 02:01:19,000
which if you get 10 people that have 11, you know, versions, is Petita.

1771
02:01:19,000 --> 02:01:21,000
Elizabeth "Betita" Sutherland Martínez's version.

1772
02:01:21,000 --> 02:01:24,000
In our book is the most coherent.

1773
02:01:24,000 --> 02:01:32,000
And I have heard people say that white people were never used to leave SNCC.

1774
02:01:32,000 --> 02:01:35,000
And I have heard multiple votes.

1775
02:01:35,000 --> 02:01:37,000
Each one contradicted the other.

1776
02:01:37,000 --> 02:01:41,000
The last one had two o'clock in the morning, so forth and so on.

1777
02:01:41,000 --> 02:01:44,000
Hers is the most coherent one.

1778
02:01:44,000 --> 02:01:48,000
And I think it's probably the most accurate one.

1779
02:01:48,000 --> 02:01:53,000
But in any case, when we went back the first time, which was 65,

1780
02:01:53,000 --> 02:02:01,000
before we left for New Haven, already there was discussion about SNCC becoming all black.

1781
02:02:01,000 --> 02:02:06,000
Were you part of those discussions, which you have a sense of?

1782
02:02:06,000 --> 02:02:07,000
Yes.

1783
02:02:07,000 --> 02:02:08,000
And since they're going on?

1784
02:02:08,000 --> 02:02:10,000
No, they weren't.

1785
02:02:10,000 --> 02:02:17,000
Well, the substantive discussions were not conducted with white people there.

1786
02:02:17,000 --> 02:02:19,000
But it was not a secret.

1787
02:02:19,000 --> 02:02:21,000
And people were saying, yes.

1788
02:02:21,000 --> 02:02:25,000
I remember, I mean, I don't remember people's names.

1789
02:02:25,000 --> 02:02:30,000
But I remember being in meetings where people would say, yes, we think it's,

1790
02:02:30,000 --> 02:02:32,000
we want to go all black.

1791
02:02:32,000 --> 02:02:37,000
Oh, I was beside myself.

1792
02:02:37,000 --> 02:02:46,000
Now that you've heard part of my whole story, I mean, I went down to marry the movement.

1793
02:02:46,000 --> 02:02:49,000
Oh, I was completely beside myself.

1794
02:02:49,000 --> 02:02:52,000
Totally, I'm beside myself.

1795
02:02:52,000 --> 02:02:53,000
Yes.

1796
02:02:53,000 --> 02:02:56,000
And then we decided, then I said to Bob,

1797
02:02:56,000 --> 02:03:01,000
I am not disappearing without a trace.

1798
02:03:01,000 --> 02:03:04,000
So we have to write something.

1799
02:03:04,000 --> 02:03:10,000
After all, who told us to write everything and keep everything with woman?

1800
02:03:10,000 --> 02:03:11,000
Right?

1801
02:03:11,000 --> 02:03:19,000
And so we were at the moment, at that moment, I think it was May 67.

1802
02:03:19,000 --> 02:03:24,000
And we had been in Alabama with this baby,

1803
02:03:24,000 --> 02:03:29,000
who was roosting there until we figured out what was going to happen to us

1804
02:03:29,000 --> 02:03:35,000
because in the meantime Anne Braden had said that they wanted us to come and work for a skip

1805
02:03:35,000 --> 02:03:38,000
with Southern Conference Educational Fund.

1806
02:03:38,000 --> 02:03:44,000
And we wanted to get, as I remember, straightened out with SNCC before we decided,

1807
02:03:44,000 --> 02:03:46,000
before we made a decision.

1808
02:03:46,000 --> 02:03:51,000
I mean, our best preference was to stay in SNCC.

1809
02:03:52,000 --> 02:04:03,000
And so we talked about it, and we decided that we would agree to work in the White community.

1810
02:04:03,000 --> 02:04:09,000
But we could not agree to being a, to surrendering our vote.

1811
02:04:09,000 --> 02:04:15,000
In other words, we would insist on being pre-jez-regular staff members in the organization,

1812
02:04:15,000 --> 02:04:18,000
and we would work in the White community.

1813
02:04:18,000 --> 02:04:25,000
And furthermore, that to do otherwise was wrong, that you can't organize white people in a vacuum,

1814
02:04:25,000 --> 02:04:28,000
that we know what happens then.

1815
02:04:28,000 --> 02:04:37,000
And I wrote that statement, and actually I read it now, and then I have to say it is extremely well done.

1816
02:04:37,000 --> 02:04:40,000
It is well done.

1817
02:04:40,000 --> 02:04:44,000
Because it's right away says we are not doing this out of sentiment,

1818
02:04:44,000 --> 02:04:47,000
and we are not doing that out of longevity.

1819
02:04:47,000 --> 02:04:52,000
After all, Bob was the first, one of the first field secretaries period,

1820
02:04:52,000 --> 02:04:55,000
and the very first White field secretary.

1821
02:04:55,000 --> 02:04:59,000
And I came on in June of 62.

1822
02:04:59,000 --> 02:05:05,000
I outdated many of the people who wanted us to leave.

1823
02:05:05,000 --> 02:05:09,000
I was there before them.

1824
02:05:09,000 --> 02:05:12,000
And we said we were willing to do that.

1825
02:05:12,000 --> 02:05:19,000
And looking back, there was only one place in Alabama, I think we could have survived.

1826
02:05:19,000 --> 02:05:24,000
And that was this little artsy-craft-seed town called Fairhope, Alabama.

1827
02:05:24,000 --> 02:05:32,000
And Bob's family lived in Daphne, Alabama.

1828
02:05:32,000 --> 02:05:39,000
And Fairhope, Alabama was further inland, maybe, I don't know, 30 or 40 miles.

1829
02:05:39,000 --> 02:05:48,000
And Fairhope, Alabama had a reputation of tolerating artists who lived there and more unconventional people.

1830
02:05:48,000 --> 02:05:52,000
And I felt maybe we had a chance there.

1831
02:05:52,000 --> 02:06:01,000
So now I was very, very afraid, and I said to Bob, I don't want to go there.

1832
02:06:01,000 --> 02:06:05,000
And said, oh, it'll be okay, it'll be okay.

1833
02:06:05,000 --> 02:06:10,000
And I said, I'm afraid we're going to be killed there.

1834
02:06:10,000 --> 02:06:16,000
And fortunately, his mother intervened.

1835
02:06:16,000 --> 02:06:24,000
And his father had a church, but he had lost several churches because he had turned into a liberal by that time.

1836
02:06:24,000 --> 02:06:28,000
He had lost many churches, I don't remember how many.

1837
02:06:28,000 --> 02:06:34,000
And his mother said to him, not to me, it's to him, I don't want you to come here to Alabama,

1838
02:06:34,000 --> 02:06:40,000
because whatever you do, we will pay the price, and we will, who knows what will happen to us.

1839
02:06:40,000 --> 02:06:45,000
And so he wouldn't listen to me at all, but he listened to her.

1840
02:06:45,000 --> 02:06:55,000
In any case, if SNCC had accepted it, we would have gone to Alabama, with his mother without his mother.

1841
02:06:55,000 --> 02:06:59,000
And the only place, as I said, I could have thought was Fairhope, Alabama.

1842
02:06:59,000 --> 02:07:04,000
Now, how long we would have lasted in Fairhope, Alabama? I have no idea.

1843
02:07:04,000 --> 02:07:11,000
It's conceivable to me that at some point, I can't live like this, goodbye.

1844
02:07:11,000 --> 02:07:14,000
I mean, everything was upper-grick.

1845
02:07:14,000 --> 02:07:24,000
And how it was going to actually work day to day, I don't know, we would have started organizing somehow in Alabama, in the White community.

1846
02:07:24,000 --> 02:07:32,000
And then we would have gone to staff meeting somewhere, where there would have been Black people, and why people we would have discussed our work.

1847
02:07:32,000 --> 02:07:40,000
Sooner or later, I think the objective would have been that we start introducing some Black people to some of these White people.

1848
02:07:40,000 --> 02:07:50,000
We would have, knowing us, we probably would have looked for situations of conflict like Laurel, like Gunn, Mississippi.

1849
02:07:51,000 --> 02:08:07,000
Who knows, you know, I mean, after all, 50 years before this, as we can tell from Robin D.G. Kelley's Hammer and Hoe, that there were organizers in Alabama.

1850
02:08:07,000 --> 02:08:11,000
And there were even interracial organizers in Alabama.

1851
02:08:11,000 --> 02:08:24,000
And according to a story that Martha Prescod Norman Noonan told us, she was able to detect traces of that interaction many decades later.

1852
02:08:24,000 --> 02:08:29,000
So, it's up for grants. I think that the chances were good that we would have been killed.

1853
02:08:29,000 --> 02:08:38,000
One of us would have been killed, or they would have set a bomb thrown a bomb in the house, and they would have tried to kill us like they did to make sure always.

1854
02:08:39,000 --> 02:08:51,000
But I'm not sure. In any case, it did go on the record. It this piece of paper did last from 67 till now.

1855
02:08:51,000 --> 02:08:53,000
And what was the vote for?

1856
02:08:53,000 --> 02:09:04,000
Well, we never got it straight. We heard all kinds of various things. We ended up, we heard there was one vote for us. Not for women.

1857
02:09:05,000 --> 02:09:12,000
So, actually, I guess I should backtrack. So, you write this statement. Bob takes it to make sure.

1858
02:09:12,000 --> 02:09:15,000
So, what was it called then? It wasn't the executive committee.

1859
02:09:15,000 --> 02:09:17,000
It was the central committee.

1860
02:09:17,000 --> 02:09:18,000
Yeah.

1861
02:09:18,000 --> 02:09:26,000
And he presented, does he talk about it, or is it just just bring the paper proposal?

1862
02:09:26,000 --> 02:09:33,000
Well, according to the minutes, the minutes are written in Danny Lyon's book.

1863
02:09:33,000 --> 02:09:40,000
So, as I remember, he made a presentation, and then he was there to leave the room.

1864
02:09:40,000 --> 02:09:43,000
And then the minutes, they talked back and forth.

1865
02:09:43,000 --> 02:09:48,000
You know, according to the minutes, people said, gee, this is a hard situation.

1866
02:09:48,000 --> 02:09:54,000
And he was there. He's very brave. He's, you know, a legend.

1867
02:09:54,000 --> 02:09:59,000
But, you know, we were moving on.

1868
02:09:59,000 --> 02:10:09,000
In that period, when you come back to Atlanta in 1965, after you thought it was born, and then it was moment in 1967,

1869
02:10:09,000 --> 02:10:12,000
when I make the formal proposal.

1870
02:10:12,000 --> 02:10:18,000
Did you have conversations about this with people that you were close to in the SNCC, like Norman?

1871
02:10:18,000 --> 02:10:32,000
Well, my overriding impression of those years was that Norman was in deep psychic distress.

1872
02:10:32,000 --> 02:10:39,000
Let's see, his breakdown. His first breakdown was in 68.

1873
02:10:40,000 --> 02:10:42,000
So, this is before his breakdown.

1874
02:10:42,000 --> 02:10:50,000
What I remember talking to him after Peg Leg Bates, and I remember, I was Dinky Forman, and he was sitting on a couch.

1875
02:10:50,000 --> 02:10:55,000
I was sitting in a court. I said, I said, don't tell me you agree with this.

1876
02:10:55,000 --> 02:11:01,000
And he didn't deny it. I said, I know you don't agree with this.

1877
02:11:01,000 --> 02:11:04,000
Yeah, but, you know, Dorothy, he called me Dorothy.

1878
02:11:04,000 --> 02:11:10,000
Dorothy, you know, he was in deep psychic distress.

1879
02:11:10,000 --> 02:11:21,000
I think he understood that where people were, he couldn't hold them back.

1880
02:11:21,000 --> 02:11:32,000
He didn't want to be in a position of holding them back, because he knew it under his own leadership abilities.

1881
02:11:32,000 --> 02:11:37,000
But he was deeply uncomfortable.

1882
02:11:37,000 --> 02:11:50,000
I think my impression is that he definitely would have preferred an interracial organization led by Black people, which is what we had.

1883
02:11:50,000 --> 02:11:57,000
Not an interracial organization where we took on AD White people from Mississippi Summer.

1884
02:11:57,000 --> 02:12:02,000
That was untenable. That was totally untenable.

1885
02:12:02,000 --> 02:12:08,000
I think that was his comfort zone. I think he was basically a class guy.

1886
02:12:08,000 --> 02:12:13,000
He was for class unity on class, around class.

1887
02:12:13,000 --> 02:12:16,000
And I think that's what his comfort zone was.

1888
02:12:16,000 --> 02:12:21,000
But he couldn't do anything to stop it, and he wouldn't.

1889
02:12:21,000 --> 02:12:26,000
But the fact that he was not out there going home meant, you know, something to people.

1890
02:12:26,000 --> 02:12:33,000
You know, he was making a statement by not making a statement.

1891
02:12:33,000 --> 02:12:36,000
And he was in difficulty.

1892
02:12:36,000 --> 02:12:40,000
I think Julian also.

1893
02:12:40,000 --> 02:12:46,000
Now, I don't remember every disc, but Julian left relatively early on.

1894
02:12:46,000 --> 02:12:50,000
I mean, I don't know. Do you know what year he left?

1895
02:12:50,000 --> 02:12:52,000
He left by 65.

1896
02:12:52,000 --> 02:12:56,000
But it was before that. It was before the election.

1897
02:12:56,000 --> 02:12:59,000
Yeah.

1898
02:12:59,000 --> 02:13:05,000
I saw a press release about and leaving SNCC.

1899
02:13:05,000 --> 02:13:11,000
And I thought, I don't know, he framed it in terms of he looked up one day in real life, he had the doing in the work.

1900
02:13:11,000 --> 02:13:13,000
So he shouldn't.

1901
02:13:13,000 --> 02:13:17,000
But I don't know if that was the only reason.

1902
02:13:17,000 --> 02:13:23,000
I don't think anybody who ever watches this, you know, that's Nick died because white people left.

1903
02:13:23,000 --> 02:13:35,000
I do think that the fact that whatever happened to SNCC causing it to disappear in three years from then

1904
02:13:35,000 --> 02:13:39,000
was a horrible tragedy for the United States.

1905
02:13:39,000 --> 02:13:46,000
And has had a deep, deep impact every decade since then.

1906
02:13:46,000 --> 02:13:52,000
And it was truly unique.

1907
02:13:52,000 --> 02:14:06,000
It definitely was a magnet for the absolute best, most creative, most innovative, most intelligent, bravest people.

1908
02:14:06,000 --> 02:14:10,000
And we've needed it desperately ever since.

1909
02:14:10,000 --> 02:14:19,000
I myself think that what happened, the fracturing was a factor.

1910
02:14:19,000 --> 02:14:22,000
But I think there were other factors.

1911
02:14:22,000 --> 02:14:30,000
And I think deep disillusionment following Atlantic City was a tremendous factor.

1912
02:14:30,000 --> 02:14:37,000
And I think, well, it sounds very simple minded.

1913
02:14:38,000 --> 02:14:49,000
In a way, it was people's faith and democracy, lowercase D, that did them in because it didn't prepare them.

1914
02:14:49,000 --> 02:14:52,000
But what was going to happen?

1915
02:14:52,000 --> 02:15:02,000
And if you look back on it and you can just see, oh, you know, you say to yourself, oh, we should have gone into Atlantic City saying,

1916
02:15:02,000 --> 02:15:10,000
and I was not in Atlantic City, we should have said, maybe this will work, but probably it won't.

1917
02:15:10,000 --> 02:15:18,000
And next month, we're, you know, but we were not thinking about that.

1918
02:15:18,000 --> 02:15:29,000
I know this, I can really think things might have moved forward better if there had just been a plan debriefing for the summer projects.

1919
02:15:29,000 --> 02:15:37,000
Students have been in the summer or something, so they could go together to debrief any.

1920
02:15:37,000 --> 02:15:42,000
And then move on back to wherever.

1921
02:15:42,000 --> 02:15:48,000
What did you involve? Do you involve selling or doing a test plan when the proposal was rejected?

1922
02:15:48,000 --> 02:15:53,000
So when it was rejected, we told Anne Braden that we were coming to work with SCEF.

1923
02:15:53,000 --> 02:15:59,000
So we moved to New Orleans where I lived for the next 17 years.

1924
02:15:59,000 --> 02:16:02,000
And we worked there for five years.

1925
02:16:02,000 --> 02:16:07,000
Work there and for SCEF for five years.

1926
02:16:07,000 --> 02:16:13,000
And Anne Braden had wanted us to take over the organization.

1927
02:16:13,000 --> 02:16:21,000
And they had this idea that we would replicate their behavior in their division of labor.

1928
02:16:21,000 --> 02:16:26,000
And they had three children, one later died.

1929
02:16:26,000 --> 02:16:33,000
But their idea of how they conducted themselves was each one was six months on the road.

1930
02:16:33,000 --> 02:16:41,000
While the other, you know, was fanning the home fires, I absolutely did not want to live like this.

1931
02:16:41,000 --> 02:16:46,000
And I felt that it had a very, very serious effect on their children.

1932
02:16:46,000 --> 02:16:49,000
And I was not about to do that to my children.

1933
02:16:49,000 --> 02:16:56,000
And furthermore, I since Bob had very little administrative ability, I did not want to end up running the whole thing.

1934
02:16:56,000 --> 02:16:58,000
Which I would have had to end up doing.

1935
02:16:58,000 --> 02:17:04,000
And he would have been on the road doing the things that he could do well, making the contacts, making the speeches.

1936
02:17:04,000 --> 02:17:10,000
I would be home raising two children and running an organization by myself.

1937
02:17:10,000 --> 02:17:13,000
No, thank you.

1938
02:17:13,000 --> 02:17:18,000
So we stayed on this project.

1939
02:17:18,000 --> 02:17:22,000
Well, I stayed home and worked from home.

1940
02:17:22,000 --> 02:17:25,000
I was an and did me a tremendous favor.

1941
02:17:25,000 --> 02:17:32,000
She insisted that I get paid separately so that I would have social security in the future.

1942
02:17:32,000 --> 02:17:39,000
And every, you know, I should think about her every month when I get my social security check, because it's thanks to her.

1943
02:17:39,000 --> 02:17:45,000
Because they were five years, they were, would have had nothing, you know, on the books.

1944
02:17:45,000 --> 02:17:48,000
And Bob still she traveled.

1945
02:17:48,000 --> 02:17:49,000
He went to Mississippi.

1946
02:17:49,000 --> 02:17:54,000
He worked on this on the Mississippi Woodcutters Association and the grassroots organizing work.

1947
02:17:54,000 --> 02:17:56,000
I stayed at home and I did stuff from home.

1948
02:17:56,000 --> 02:17:59,000
I wrote, I did all the things that Fve always done.

1949
02:17:59,000 --> 02:18:02,000
You know, I wrote pamphlets. I wrote things.

1950
02:18:02,000 --> 02:18:07,000
I was, I have it down in that piece of paper.

1951
02:18:07,000 --> 02:18:14,000
And then finally, after we had been in civil rights, we had been professional civil rights workers for ten years.

1952
02:18:14,000 --> 02:18:19,000
I said to Bob, we have to become regular people.

1953
02:18:19,000 --> 02:18:24,000
You know, I felt like we were going to levitate into the sky.

1954
02:18:24,000 --> 02:18:28,000
You know, I mean, nobody was standing there saying you'd better get up at seven o'clock.

1955
02:18:28,000 --> 02:18:36,000
You have a clock to punch. You know, we were, if we had gone on much longer, we wouldn't have been able to integrate back into the regular world.

1956
02:18:36,000 --> 02:18:42,000
And there's something about long term organizers, you know, where they're, they don't have regular routines.

1957
02:18:42,000 --> 02:18:48,000
It sometimes separates them from the people who do, you know, the people that they're organizing.

1958
02:18:48,000 --> 02:18:55,000
So he became a carpenter. He was a carpenter and he was able to join the union.

1959
02:18:55,000 --> 02:19:02,000
And I went to nursing school to be a practical nurse.

1960
02:19:02,000 --> 02:19:11,000
And then of course, we continued doing stuff, you know, as volunteers and some local struggles that we had.

1961
02:19:11,000 --> 02:19:20,000
And local struggles that we got involved in, but we had other, other work, other jobs.

1962
02:19:20,000 --> 02:19:26,000
So can we go back? Sure.

1963
02:19:26,000 --> 02:19:34,000
So you're looking, so can you tell us about the civil liberties workshops that you organized?

1964
02:19:34,000 --> 02:19:38,000
I guess it was carried off in summer of 1963.

1965
02:19:38,000 --> 02:19:41,000
I think it was the spring. It was the spring of 1963.

1966
02:19:41,000 --> 02:19:48,000
Well, that turned out to be a totally unsung but very important episode in SNCC's history.

1967
02:19:48,000 --> 02:19:55,000
I think I'm the only one who's written about it. So far, I'm sure there'll be other people down the road.

1968
02:19:55,000 --> 02:20:03,000
It's the product of this very close relationship that Anne Braden and Miss Baker had.

1969
02:20:03,000 --> 02:20:09,000
And they were survivors of McCarthyism.

1970
02:20:09,000 --> 02:20:15,000
And McCarthyism was not dead. McCarthyism was very much alive at the time.

1971
02:20:15,000 --> 02:20:20,000
Although in retrospect, it was waning.

1972
02:20:20,000 --> 02:20:28,000
And I don't know when the last, well, let's see.

1973
02:20:28,000 --> 02:20:37,000
I think the House of American Activities Committee was still having hearings even up to 1964, if I'm not mistaken.

1974
02:20:37,000 --> 02:20:43,000
Where the back was really broken by a group called Women's Strike for Peace.

1975
02:20:43,000 --> 02:20:48,000
And that was in the early 60s, 61 or 62. I'd have to check that.

1976
02:20:48,000 --> 02:21:00,000
And previously, people who were called before the Un-American Activities Committee were faced with two very unpleasant options.

1977
02:21:00,000 --> 02:21:04,000
First of all, they had to get lawyers. Couldn't go into a hearing with that lawyer.

1978
02:21:04,000 --> 02:21:11,000
You had two options. You could take the Fifth Amendment, which is your guaranteed constitutional rights,

1979
02:21:11,000 --> 02:21:20,000
and which the American Miss Media would make equivalent to being, to be saying you're guilty.

1980
02:21:20,000 --> 02:21:23,000
You know, and all the mafia peoples took the Fifth Amendment.

1981
02:21:23,000 --> 02:21:26,000
Anybody who didn't want to go to jail took the Fifth Amendment.

1982
02:21:26,000 --> 02:21:32,000
Or you took the First Amendment, and you had no protection whatsoever, and you could be cited for contempt of Congress.

1983
02:21:32,000 --> 02:21:37,000
Which is what happened to Carl Braden and Frank Wilkinson. They went to jail for a year.

1984
02:21:38,000 --> 02:21:52,000
So there were very few protections. Previously to this, in the 50s, flying out of my head, Charles "Charlie" Jones.

1985
02:21:52,000 --> 02:22:01,000
Yes, before he joined SNCC. And he had been a super patriot of some kind, and he had testified.

1986
02:22:02,000 --> 02:22:13,000
By 19, by N was completely committed to fighting these investigating committees and fighting McCarthyism.

1987
02:22:13,000 --> 02:22:19,000
And parenthetically, make sure I come back to this when I was living in New Orleans.

1988
02:22:19,000 --> 02:22:30,000
I wrote a paper in when I was briefly in graduate school about the Eastland hearings that took place in 1954 against the Southern Conference Educational Fund.

1989
02:22:31,000 --> 02:22:42,000
So in 1954, sorry, 1954 was probably the height of McCarthyism, 1954, 55, 56.

1990
02:22:42,000 --> 02:22:47,000
And they did everything they could to smear the civil rights movement.

1991
02:22:47,000 --> 02:22:58,000
So Ann was a survivor of this, and Miss Baker was, I don't think she was ever, they ever thought of calling her, but Ann was always in danger of being called.

1992
02:22:59,000 --> 02:23:16,000
And Carl had gone to jail for a year. So they clipped up together that it was very important to have some internal education about what SNCC was going to do, if it was ever called by an investigating committee.

1993
02:23:16,000 --> 02:23:26,000
And it turned out this was extremely important. And there was, I think the conference went on for at least two days, as I remember.

1994
02:23:26,000 --> 02:23:46,000
I had no idea what the actual process was, but I remember a lot of agonized discussion. And whether SNCC could admit people without loyalty oaths, whether it had to be concerned about people's politics, volunteers, politics.

1995
02:23:46,000 --> 02:23:58,000
And then Allard K. Lowenstein was around and who had already told Bob Moses, I believe, no, no, he was around the next summer.

1996
02:23:58,000 --> 02:24:09,000
But there were people always coming up, there were always rumors and people coming up to form and to Bob Moses saying, oh, watch out, this one, this one is red, that one's red and so forth.

1997
02:24:09,000 --> 02:24:19,000
So we had this agonizing discussion and Bob at that time was very nervous about having white people, Bob Moses coming in because of the danger to the local people.

1998
02:24:19,000 --> 02:24:26,000
And he was doubly nervous about having anybody who was called a communist coming in also for the same reason.

1999
02:24:26,000 --> 02:24:35,000
And there was a lot of agonized discussion, but at the end people decided that they would not cooperate. This was a stunning victory.

2000
02:24:35,000 --> 02:24:43,000
Unbeknownst to, I mean, this is totally has gone without any historic, I think I'm the first one who wrote about it.

2001
02:24:43,000 --> 02:24:57,000
And I am convinced that there was, there had to be an undercover agent there and that the, it was transmitted to the government that if these people were subpoenaed, they would refuse to cooperate.

2002
02:24:57,000 --> 02:25:08,000
And then in 1963, there was still an incredible amount of goodwill in reserve in the country for the Sid and Heroes.

2003
02:25:08,000 --> 02:25:20,000
And it would not have looked good internationally to have Sid and Heroes go to jail sent by the U.S. government because they refused to talk about their views.

2004
02:25:20,000 --> 02:25:23,000
That would have definitely looked very bad.

2005
02:25:23,000 --> 02:25:32,000
What was the one of the biggest issues about whether or not to, you know, how a Facebook would affect somebody who is nice to us.

2006
02:25:32,000 --> 02:25:42,000
Yes. Yes. Well, that's what I've said. There was, there was pressure about that, about people's views. They decided, no, they were not going to have an oath.

2007
02:25:42,000 --> 02:25:50,000
And furthermore, if they were called by a committee, they would not take the Fifth Amendment. They would take a first man that they would go to jail.

2008
02:25:50,000 --> 02:26:03,000
And later on Julian told me many years later that in the 60s and this woman, he said the 70s, he, and he was never able to verify this because I asked him within the past couple of years about it.

2009
02:26:03,000 --> 02:26:12,000
He said he had read somewhere that the government had 6,500 black informers well over the country.

2010
02:26:12,000 --> 02:26:25,000
So we had to have an informer. And that person probably still, if that person is still alive, they have not been un-messed. And we still got him, somebody.

2011
02:26:25,000 --> 02:26:44,000
There was something that happened before that workshop. There was maybe in 62, maybe fall 62. Carl Braden was in Mississippi and there was a lot of newspaper coverage about, you know, red, calm, you know, how they put it.

2012
02:26:44,000 --> 02:26:54,000
But coverage of that and there was, like, you know, those are really concerned. But do you remember that?

2013
02:26:54,000 --> 02:27:01,000
I don't. I don't remember that particular thing. But I know, I remember, he was very concerned. He was very concerned.

2014
02:27:01,000 --> 02:27:10,000
But he was never concerned from the point of view that, oh, I can't have these people around and, oh, they're going to, you know, screw up what we're doing.

2015
02:27:10,000 --> 02:27:23,000
It was solely because of the danger that it presented to local people. And by then, you know, Herbert Lee had been killed. So that's a whole other story, you know, about walking around feeling responsible.

2016
02:27:23,000 --> 02:27:38,000
So I think it was a protective measure. And I honestly, I don't know. That was the fall of 62, you said. I should be able to remember that, but I don't remember that.

2017
02:27:38,000 --> 02:27:46,000
Can you talk about what you were trying to do when you were interviewing people to go to someone else?

2018
02:27:46,000 --> 02:28:01,000
Oh, yes. Well, like I said in the movie, I mean, it's in the movie. I mean, we were very, very hard-headed about it. We did not want crazies. And we didn't want deep us.

2019
02:28:01,000 --> 02:28:12,000
Now, I think we succeeded pretty well because I think of the hundreds of people who were there. I think there were a few divas.

2020
02:28:12,000 --> 02:28:25,000
And there might have been a few crazies. But considering the high percentage that they could have been, I think we kept it down. Now, I was only in one place. I don't know what other people were doing around the country.

2021
02:28:25,000 --> 02:28:40,000
My impression is that it ranged from being very hands-on to very loose and that there were some places where people just said, you know, go.

2022
02:28:40,000 --> 02:28:47,000
But not oh, we were totally rigorous.

2023
02:28:47,000 --> 02:28:49,000
Say the lick.

2024
02:28:49,000 --> 02:28:58,000
Oh, yes. Well, we had a questionnaire which I believe was prepared by COFO. We didn't do that.

2025
02:28:58,000 --> 02:29:13,000
See, our whole way of functioning was we were taking direction from the center, from the hub. So it would have been unheard of for me to write an application for somebody.

2026
02:29:13,000 --> 02:29:25,000
This was written by people in Mississippi. And we interviewed every one of them personally. And usually they were two of us, a black person and a white person.

2027
02:29:25,000 --> 02:29:43,000
And we wrote detailed reports, which and who knows. I think I know where they are, but I don't know. And I'm certainly hoping that they're uncovered after I'm in my grave because some of them were not very flattering. Let's put it that way.

2028
02:29:43,000 --> 02:29:54,000
So what we were looking for was to make sure that nobody was an adventurer. Like, oh, I think Fll do something exciting. Fll go to Mississippi.

2029
02:29:54,000 --> 02:30:02,000
We wanted people who were going to be respectful of the black communities, even if they didn't understand the thing about black communities.

2030
02:30:02,000 --> 02:30:12,000
And the way we put it, we put it in very, very simple concrete terms. Are you going to wear shorts to church?

2031
02:30:12,000 --> 02:30:25,000
Those kind of examples to see how, I mean, I don't know how clever we were because, you know, you didn't have to be a brain surgeon, certainly not Ben Carson, to figure out, you know, what the correct answer was.

2032
02:30:25,000 --> 02:30:31,000
But we were also looking at them and seeing their body language and their reaction.

2033
02:30:31,000 --> 02:30:40,000
We wanted people who would behave, who would behave, and who would realize that they were going into a very dangerous situation.

2034
02:30:40,000 --> 02:30:50,000
Now, you know that in this last reunion, a woman came up to me who I did not know at all. She said, I know you don't know.

2035
02:30:50,000 --> 02:30:56,000
I'm talking about recently in Mississippi. She said, you don't know who I am, but you interviewed me.

2036
02:30:56,000 --> 02:31:07,000
There were several people who came up to me. And she said, I have to say, Fve never forgotten it in my whole life. I said, oh my God, what did I do?

2037
02:31:07,000 --> 02:31:15,000
She said, you scared the hell out of me. You said, are you ready to die?

2038
02:31:15,000 --> 02:31:32,000
So I said, oh, well, in that case, that's so bad. So she said, you, so I said, you mean, I didn't send you down here on false pretenses.

2039
02:31:32,000 --> 02:31:40,000
She said, no, no, you didn't. She said it was one of the worst things I ever went through.

2040
02:31:40,000 --> 02:31:45,000
She said, but the good thing is she said, when I give an interview, I remember what you did.

2041
02:31:45,000 --> 02:31:53,000
And I tell the truth and I bear to honor people. We did, oh, we did, we did, we did.

2042
02:31:53,000 --> 02:32:00,000
Because in my mind, I mean, I didn't also want to be responsible. Oh my God, you let this person go through.

2043
02:32:00,000 --> 02:32:07,000
I'm sure that if we aired, we aired on the other side, of course, and we probably didn't let some people go down.

2044
02:32:07,000 --> 02:32:13,000
Who should have, now the one person I slipped up on was Abbie Hoffman.

2045
02:32:13,000 --> 02:32:21,000
We let Abbie Hoffman through, but at that time he was wearing a suit and tie. I mean, he was a completely different person.

2046
02:32:21,000 --> 02:32:32,000
And he, ironically, is the only one that I'm sure I've told you this, that I know who actually went public after white people left SNCC,

2047
02:32:32,000 --> 02:32:42,000
gnashing his teeth about how terribly he had been treated as a white person. Yes, in the village voice. Yes, yes, yes.

2048
02:32:43,000 --> 02:32:52,000
Well, the question was whether he ever in SNCC. I mean, by stretching, I mean, that's the thing. People ask me now.

2049
02:32:52,000 --> 02:33:00,000
It was so and so in Snick, so I said, well, what do you mean in Snick? I said, do you understand that we didn't have members? Oh, what?

2050
02:33:00,000 --> 02:33:05,000
So we didn't have members. We had to stay.

2051
02:33:05,000 --> 02:33:14,000
So there's a lot of wishy, you know, mushyness about that. If you were in a project in Mississippi and you were in a freedom school,

2052
02:33:14,000 --> 02:33:27,000
were you in SNCC? You were in a cofo project to be, you know, actually accurate. But he was one of the few he said, and he was a volunteer.

2053
02:33:28,000 --> 02:33:35,000
I don't know, but this is easy to find out. It's in this stuff, and you should definitely look up that in the village voice.

2054
02:33:35,000 --> 02:33:43,000
And the other person, I think, who had bad things to say was Susan Brownmiller, if I remember, there were two of them.

2055
02:33:43,000 --> 02:33:50,000
Two of them. Now she was not SNCC, but she had a lot of bad things to say about white people being used and four white people and four white people.

2056
02:33:51,000 --> 02:33:59,000
So after all of that episode, you know, there were press who wanted to interview us. We said, no, we never, we were never interviewed.

2057
02:33:59,000 --> 02:34:09,000
And I just want to clarify that what happened to white people, you know, it ends up everybody's crying over the poor white people, you know.

2058
02:34:09,000 --> 02:34:16,000
If we all look back, it was, is it a surprise after what happened in Atlantic City, really?

2059
02:34:17,000 --> 02:34:25,000
And would we have not done the same ourselves very likely so?

2060
02:34:27,000 --> 02:34:45,000
So that's why it always held me back from crying. I mean, I was always loyal to SNCC, but also, I can't say for 100% that I wouldn't, if I had gone through what they went through, I don't know what I would have done.

2061
02:34:46,000 --> 02:34:54,000
And I mean, Bob Moses is a suggestion about getting all the volunteers together, that would have been helpful. It would have been helpful.

2062
02:34:54,000 --> 02:35:01,000
I mean, you see him, Bob Moses, in this very sad in the movie.

2063
02:35:05,000 --> 02:35:10,000
What's the other movie about the Freedom Summer? It's just slip my mind.

2064
02:35:11,000 --> 02:35:20,000
The older one, the older one. Freedom on my mind. He's standing there, I've seen the film several times, he's standing there with the clipboard.

2065
02:35:20,000 --> 02:35:28,000
He's in, in, in, in, in Atlantic City. He's keeping track of all the different delegations and the boats.

2066
02:35:28,000 --> 02:35:34,000
And he looks at the camera and he says, if things go along the way we expect, we're going to win.

2067
02:35:35,000 --> 02:35:46,000
So if everybody, and certainly somebody of Bob Moses is a stature, thought we're going to win, was anybody going to say, hey, wait a second, what if we don't win?

2068
02:35:46,000 --> 02:35:51,000
What are we going to do? What is the plan B? And we didn't have one. We didn't have one.

2069
02:35:51,000 --> 02:36:00,000
Given all of that, is it any wonder? Now, some people feel, I don't know if Judy may feel, or the people may feel that,

2070
02:36:01,000 --> 02:36:06,000
going, that becoming all black was a natural thing and needed to be done. It should have been done.

2071
02:36:09,000 --> 02:36:19,000
I don't think I agree. I think, I think we were a powerhouse when you think of what we were able to do.

2072
02:36:19,000 --> 02:36:23,000
It's not because we had all those white people, because we didn't have all those white people.

2073
02:36:23,000 --> 02:36:28,000
I don't think until the summer of 64, we had more than 20% of the people who were white, maybe 25.

2074
02:36:31,000 --> 02:36:41,000
I think there were some very good lessons that we taught. We taught that a black person can tell a white person what to do.

2075
02:36:41,000 --> 02:36:54,000
That was unheard of. That was unheard of. We were taught people by example, that if the context changes, then people's behavior can change.

2076
02:36:55,000 --> 02:37:08,000
That was unheard of. I tell people that we probably, for those brief years, are the only Americans who ever experienced racial equality.

2077
02:37:10,000 --> 02:37:20,000
I mean, or maybe equality is not the right word, that we achieved in the South African term, a non-racial community.

2078
02:37:21,000 --> 02:37:32,000
Not because we weren't racial, because everybody knew and was conscious of that, but because the context was, if you're going to be with us, you're going to take a bullet.

2079
02:37:33,000 --> 02:37:37,000
You can take a bullet as a white person or a black person.

2080
02:37:38,000 --> 02:37:46,000
It was unique, really, when you think about it. I mean, what other group was it like that? I think we taught a lot.

2081
02:37:47,000 --> 02:37:55,000
The country so deeply racist that whether we could have remained that way, obviously we didn't. We couldn't.

2082
02:37:55,000 --> 02:38:06,000
It was racism that did us in. People have different ideas about why SNCC came to an end. There's a lot of this, a lot of contention about that still.

2083
02:38:07,000 --> 02:38:18,000
I think there were many, many reasons, but the basic reason really was this is a profoundly racial, racially disturbed country.

2084
02:38:20,000 --> 02:38:29,000
In order to really get through it, we're going to have to have Black Lives Matter times a million.

2085
02:38:30,000 --> 02:38:38,000
We're going to have to take it on every which way, culturally, socially, physically, academically, every way.

2086
02:38:41,000 --> 02:38:50,000
Otherwise, that's the vacuum. The vacuum is racism. Then all kinds of people walk into the vacuum.

2087
02:38:51,000 --> 02:38:58,000
So I still feel sorry that SNCC is lost. There was loss. I don't know if other people do.

2088
02:38:59,000 --> 02:39:05,000
And I think it may play out in a lot of racial ways. They play out.

2089
02:39:06,000 --> 02:39:15,000
There's certainly an awful lot of confusion about what happened. And you know there was confusion right away after Peg Leg Bates. Within two weeks they were debates.

2090
02:39:16,000 --> 02:39:21,000
This vote happened. This vote didn't happen. All of that. I don't know how we would ever.

2091
02:39:22,000 --> 02:39:34,000
I don't think there was any kind of coherent note taking there. Doesn't seem that anybody, you know, everybody can agree with it.

2092
02:39:35,000 --> 02:39:41,000
Everybody can adhere to it. But I don't want this, there my interview to be only on to end on that note.

2093
02:39:42,000 --> 02:39:50,000
Because it's not the critical thing. It's not the critical thing. What happened to the poor white people? What happened to poor us? You know, that's not the critical thing.

2094
02:39:51,000 --> 02:40:10,000
The critical thing is that I think that we showed that without sounding hyper lowercase democratic, we showed that there is an incredible resource and reservoir of real,

2095
02:40:11,000 --> 02:40:24,000
creativity and ingenuity. Certainly in the black community and in the white community that is willing to support black liberation.

2096
02:40:25,000 --> 02:40:33,000
And it's there. It's still there. It's there. And it's definitely a different times it's going to come out.

2097
02:40:33,000 --> 02:40:40,000
And people have hopes that each time it will be the time that we can recreate that each time.

2098
02:40:42,000 --> 02:40:54,000
So you say that you're not someone who works here today. It feels to me like you're fulfilling the charge that's meant to let people work in our community.

2099
02:40:55,000 --> 02:41:07,000
Well, since, let's see, I'm for 13 years. I've been doing this mostly. You know, that's what I do.

2100
02:41:08,000 --> 02:41:20,000
In addition to my job is work in speaking out as a Jewish person about Israel, Palestine. And I've come a long way in those 12 or 13 years and learned in a lot.

2101
02:41:21,000 --> 02:41:34,000
My initial impetus was to do what's next said to do, which we, as you can tell, we were ready to do it. We said at least in 1957, it never came about.

2102
02:41:35,000 --> 02:41:50,000
In the 60s, 67s, sorry. In the Gris, in the Grel project, we tried to do white organizing in a moment of crisis in Mississippi.

2103
02:41:51,000 --> 02:41:58,000
And I would say we, and I use that sort of in quotes because I was home with children and I was not traveling to Mississippi.

2104
02:41:59,000 --> 02:42:07,000
There were several men who were doing that in different, to different degrees of effectiveness.

2105
02:42:12,000 --> 02:42:25,000
So we, I took a tart. This is, this is what I have to do. This is what people expect me to do. And I have to say, there are not a whole lot of SNCC people who say to me, oh, I'm going to join you.

2106
02:42:26,000 --> 02:42:40,000
But I have yet in 12, 13 years to have one SNCC person ever say, I don't agree with what you're doing. And many of them have said, good for you that you're doing it because it's tough.

2107
02:42:41,000 --> 02:42:54,000
It's tough without having some of the benefits that SNCC have. Because even while we were right there in the middle of it, I, I knew at least I'm presumed other people knew that if I lived to be a million,

2108
02:42:55,000 --> 02:43:04,000
would I ever be able to sit in a room with people like this? I mean, almost every one of them outdazzled the other one.

2109
02:43:05,000 --> 02:43:20,000
And that's the other lesson takeaway that I tell people. You know, snakes stood everything. And in addition to having black people telling why people were to do, it showed you that a person with a third grade education might be smarter than a PhD.

2110
02:43:20,000 --> 02:43:40,000
And this is very useful to know. There were a lot of things that were stood on their heads. And that, those are all carry ways. We don't have that in this movement. And I have definitely, I've told kids, I've brought kids lessons from those days.

2111
02:43:40,000 --> 02:43:50,000
And I've said, you have to take care of each other. You have to send people away on R&R. That's what James Forman did. James Forman invented that. He invented that.

2112
02:43:52,000 --> 02:44:01,000
We don't have, you know, while you walk into a room and say, oh, here we are. We're all together. We can get sustenance until we go out the next time. We don't have that.

2113
02:44:01,000 --> 02:44:11,000
Because when we're out there, we're out there on the front lines with people who hate us, hate us, vicious and hateful people.

2114
02:44:12,000 --> 02:44:27,000
And actually, it was one of the women in our book, one of the black women, who told me that she was in a demonstration in Israel years ago, of progressive, with progressive Israeli Jews.

2115
02:44:27,000 --> 02:44:34,000
And she said, the abuse they have suffered there was worse than anything she ever went through in the cell.

2116
02:44:36,000 --> 02:44:42,000
And people ask me about that. And I said, well, the difference is they didn't talk to you much. They just tried to kill you.

2117
02:44:43,000 --> 02:44:52,000
And here they abuse you. They don't, up until now, have not tried to kill the abuse level is extremely high.

2118
02:44:53,000 --> 02:44:59,000
So I can't say that I go home and I rarely am able to say to myself, wow, we did great things.

2119
02:45:00,000 --> 02:45:10,000
But I say, well, we did it, at least we did it. And hopefully it's going to mean something someday. I think it is starting to mean something.

2120
02:45:13,000 --> 02:45:17,000
Can you tell me about Ruby Doris from Robinson?

2121
02:45:18,000 --> 02:45:29,000
Yes, I met her, probably the winter of, I met her before I was on stiff. I met her when we were in the loft.

2122
02:45:30,000 --> 02:45:40,000
You know about the loft. People have forgotten about the loft. First we had the windowless cubicle, then we had the loft, then we had Raymond Street.

2123
02:45:41,000 --> 02:45:49,000
There might have been something in between. So I met her in the loft, which was also on Auburn Avenue, I believe.

2124
02:45:50,000 --> 02:45:58,000
And so if that's the winter of 61, 62, I don't know when she got out of jail from Rock Hill.

2125
02:45:59,000 --> 02:46:03,000
It was in spring of 61.

2126
02:46:04,000 --> 02:46:05,000
Spring of 61.

2127
02:46:06,000 --> 02:46:19,000
Okay, well when she came into the office, there was a murmur because she had a tremendous reputation as being brave as a lion.

2128
02:46:20,000 --> 02:46:25,000
In those days, brave as any man or a brave verb than any man.

2129
02:46:26,000 --> 02:46:30,000
Probably, I don't know, for sure.

2130
02:46:35,000 --> 02:46:43,000
So how do some of Ruby and I until Ruby got sick, I think Ruby didn't really like me very much.

2131
02:46:44,000 --> 02:46:48,000
But put up with me because I was a very hard worker.

2132
02:46:49,000 --> 02:46:58,000
Later on, Cynthia Griggs Fleming, when Cynthia Griggs Fleming did her book about Ruby, she called me and she wanted an interview and she said,

2133
02:46:59,000 --> 02:47:04,000
the word is that I get is that you were one of the few white women that Ruby liked.

2134
02:47:06,000 --> 02:47:11,000
So liking was different from respecting.

2135
02:47:12,000 --> 02:47:18,000
We never socialized. I don't think we ever had three minutes of chitchat.

2136
02:47:19,000 --> 02:47:27,000
It was work and she was very fierce, very awesome and fierce.

2137
02:47:28,000 --> 02:47:33,000
And I like everybody else was afraid of her. It was a little afraid of her.

2138
02:47:34,000 --> 02:47:40,000
But she was never, there was never anything I had to be afraid of because I did my work. That was the main thing with Ruby.

2139
02:47:41,000 --> 02:47:46,000
I was doing your work. I always did my work.

2140
02:47:46,000 --> 02:47:51,000
But when Ruby got sick, then we became friends.

2141
02:47:52,000 --> 02:48:01,000
Well, Ruby was, even without having the title to go with it, she was sort of second to form it.

2142
02:48:02,000 --> 02:48:09,000
And in modern terms, she did a lot of personnel work.

2143
02:48:09,000 --> 02:48:15,000
And she kept track of where people were and what they were doing, what they were supposed to be doing.

2144
02:48:17,000 --> 02:48:24,000
And she did financial planning to the extent that we had any financial planning with James Forman.

2145
02:48:25,000 --> 02:48:27,000
He respected her a lot.

2146
02:48:29,000 --> 02:48:36,000
I'm not sure if I would call her an even keeled person. I don't think she was.

2147
02:48:36,000 --> 02:48:44,000
She was very emotional and she had obviously had trauma.

2148
02:48:45,000 --> 02:48:52,000
I think that 30 days of chipping or breaking racks was an unbearable trauma for her.

2149
02:48:53,000 --> 02:48:57,000
And she went to porch. Yes, and she went to porch.

2150
02:48:58,000 --> 02:49:05,000
So, not to me. No, she never, when we became sort of friends,

2151
02:49:06,000 --> 02:49:13,000
there was a lot of barriers that came down. She was flat on her back at this real hospital.

2152
02:49:14,000 --> 02:49:20,000
And I came in there. And I was, I mean, this is long before I became a nurse.

2153
02:49:21,000 --> 02:49:27,000
Some people are afraid of sick people and some people aren't.

2154
02:49:28,000 --> 02:49:35,000
And the people who were afraid, they stayed away. And then they were the people who weren't.

2155
02:49:36,000 --> 02:49:41,000
We were living in New Haven then. But we would come to New York very often.

2156
02:49:42,000 --> 02:49:46,000
And my parents, we stayed at my parents' house and they lived one block from Beth Israel.

2157
02:49:47,000 --> 02:49:50,000
So, I was able to get over there a lot.

2158
02:49:51,000 --> 02:49:55,000
And at one point, she was a holy terror in the hospital.

2159
02:49:56,000 --> 02:50:05,000
And the nurses wanted to do something and she refused. She jumped out of bed, trailing all these IV things and ripping them out.

2160
02:50:07,000 --> 02:50:10,000
Looking back, I just, I mean, here she was in New York.

2161
02:50:11,000 --> 02:50:15,000
But I don't know why she was in New York, week after week after week in the hospital.

2162
02:50:16,000 --> 02:50:21,000
It's hard to believe that she couldn't, they couldn't have, he floned her home. I don't know.

2163
02:50:22,000 --> 02:50:25,000
Here she had a little boy by then. She had a husband by then.

2164
02:50:26,000 --> 02:50:30,000
And here day after day after day, she said, I think she was in there for weeks, weeks.

2165
02:50:31,000 --> 02:50:40,000
So, then things, then Ruby was not, she became gentle.

2166
02:50:41,000 --> 02:50:49,000
And, you know, we talked, we laughed, we talked about, oh, you know, so and so can you believe so and so's up to this?

2167
02:50:50,000 --> 02:50:51,000
Oh, tell me about it girl, you know, that kind of thing.

2168
02:50:53,000 --> 02:50:55,000
You would Ruby dollars gasping.

2169
02:50:56,000 --> 02:51:04,000
Yes, and then for me would come. And the three of us would, our heads would be bent over and we would, you would be telling funny stories and out.

2170
02:51:05,000 --> 02:51:10,000
And he was very, he was very kind to her. He was very, he was very gentle with her.

2171
02:51:12,000 --> 02:51:21,000
And, and I don't know, I actually spoke to her sister, whose name I can't think of right at the moment.

2172
02:51:22,000 --> 02:51:35,000
Mary Ann, who is a doctor. And when we had the SNCC reunion, I, I think I tried to talk to her about what the medical issues were, which always was a mystery to me.

2173
02:51:36,000 --> 02:51:44,000
I think it was a form of leukemia. It was very, it was virulent. I mean, I think she got sick within two years she was dead.

2174
02:51:45,000 --> 02:51:53,000
When she died, we were already living in the South, back in the South, we went in New Orleans, we came out of the New Orleans.

2175
02:51:54,000 --> 02:52:06,000
And I remember that funeral, oh, oh, oh, so of course they had her hair done. That was the number one thing, first of all, had the corpse, she had her hair straightened as a corpse.

2176
02:52:06,000 --> 02:52:13,000
And she, in her, in her life, she was one of the first people who wore a natural, she always wore her hair natural.

2177
02:52:15,000 --> 02:52:26,000
So she hardly even looked like herself. I could hardly go up there. Oh God, what a nightmare that was. And then we went, we were outside after was I completely broke down, sob, sob, sob.

2178
02:52:27,000 --> 02:52:35,000
Casey Hayden. Why are you crying so much? She said, don't cry so much. I cried a lot.

2179
02:52:37,000 --> 02:52:47,000
So there was a view, I think, form in hell, this I didn't agree with this, you know, that, that, I don't know if she was poisoned or the government did something.

2180
02:52:47,000 --> 02:52:55,000
And I think her immune system just completely crashed from what happened to her in the prison, but mostly in, in breaking rocks.

2181
02:52:55,000 --> 02:53:06,000
I was later, they explained to me from side to side on the road. I mean it was completely useless, useless, useless, harassing, horrible physical work.

2182
02:53:10,000 --> 02:53:21,000
So she was, she was a complicated character. I did. Katherine Ruby Zellner.

2183
02:53:22,000 --> 02:53:35,000
And also, I left her father's mother, so it was after two people. So she was a very, she was a difficult, passionate person.

2184
02:53:38,000 --> 02:53:48,000
And she really cared. Now to think that she got, now I appreciate that she got married and had a child and worked for SNCC

2185
02:53:48,000 --> 02:53:54,000
And managed to keep all of that going somehow. I mean really my hat's up to her.

2186
02:53:55,000 --> 02:54:02,000
And then I don't know how many months she was sick, and she was, I think she was 26 when she died.

2187
02:54:02,000 --> 02:54:10,000
She had to have been sick a year, because I know she was in the hospital for weeks and weeks and weeks, in New York.

2188
02:54:10,000 --> 02:54:15,000
So she didn't have much time, she had 25 years, you know.

2189
02:54:18,000 --> 02:54:26,000
Now I don't remember her being a big architect of policy, but maybe she was in meetings that I wasn't.

2190
02:54:26,000 --> 02:54:33,000
I knew it probably no more than I would. But she, she's the one that I remember, she'd say.

2191
02:54:33,000 --> 02:54:41,000
I mean if you look at some of the minutes, she'd say, where are the floaters? She said, she wanted to know where.

2192
02:54:42,000 --> 02:54:48,000
Where, what is someone so doing? When I used to answer the phone, people had to speak.

2193
02:54:48,000 --> 02:54:51,000
That said, Ruby wants to talk to you.

2194
02:54:54,000 --> 02:54:59,000
The men were petrified of her. Petrified.

2195
02:55:02,000 --> 02:55:08,000
So how did you feel about going into the Mississippi Freedom Summer after you did the interview?

2196
02:55:08,000 --> 02:55:15,000
I was terrified. I was terrified. I spent weeks imagining, oh I thought, can I only get run over?

2197
02:55:15,000 --> 02:55:19,000
If I got run over and just broke my foot, what's so bad about that?

2198
02:55:19,000 --> 02:55:24,000
She was the draft Audrey. She was the pick yourself out of the action.

2199
02:55:24,000 --> 02:55:28,000
Yeah, and here I was here. I mean, you talk about a psychological issue.

2200
02:55:28,000 --> 02:55:35,000
Here I was, I was vetting people to go to a place that I myself was terrified about going, was hoping something would happen.

2201
02:55:36,000 --> 02:55:40,000
No, no, it was terrible, terrible. And ever since I'll never be the same.

2202
02:55:40,000 --> 02:55:47,000
When I've ever seen that sign, I'm there. Here it is years and years later, after handed to you for living in that place.

2203
02:55:51,000 --> 02:55:56,000
But I mean, I don't think it's worse than Alabama. My heart didn't drop when I went to Alabama.

2204
02:55:56,000 --> 02:56:00,000
They kill you in Alabama just as much.

2205
02:56:01,000 --> 02:56:05,000
Well, you know, the other day I was talking about terrorism.

2206
02:56:05,000 --> 02:56:12,000
I said, we're the only ones who really, we're the ones who have been victims of terror.

2207
02:56:12,000 --> 02:56:24,000
If you define terror as violence against the civilian population to create fear for a political objective.

2208
02:56:25,000 --> 02:56:31,000
If that's terrorism, we had nothing but terrorism.

2209
02:56:31,000 --> 02:56:36,000
But of course, they're not terrorists because they white people and they're the terrorists.

2210
02:56:36,000 --> 02:56:43,000
In fact, this group, the one who killed the people in South Carolina, he was not a terrorist.

2211
02:56:43,000 --> 02:56:49,000
The white people are crazy. It's the Muslims and the black people who are terrorists.

2212
02:56:49,000 --> 02:56:54,000
You were talking about the difference in how people perceive who the terrorists.

2213
02:56:54,000 --> 02:56:56,000
Yeah.

2214
02:56:56,000 --> 02:57:00,000
What was your work in Mississippi that summer?

2215
02:57:00,000 --> 02:57:08,000
In Mississippi, I was one of the people on the WATS line. I did my eight hours. I did the first eight.

2216
02:57:08,000 --> 02:57:11,000
What did that entail?

2217
02:57:11,000 --> 02:57:19,000
Was that entail keeping track of people who were arrested?

2218
02:57:19,000 --> 02:57:30,000
Doing some minimal work with FBI, such as they were, being a press contact.

2219
02:57:30,000 --> 02:57:38,000
That was it.

2220
02:57:38,000 --> 02:57:42,000
I mean, the three of us split up the WATS line.

2221
02:57:42,000 --> 02:57:45,000
Judy and Betty and me.

2222
02:57:45,000 --> 02:57:51,000
So I did seven to three or nine to five, whatever.

2223
02:57:51,000 --> 02:57:56,000
So basically, we're a contact for the parents, for the local people.

2224
02:57:56,000 --> 02:58:01,000
I mean, the people local in the areas that the volunteers came from.

2225
02:58:01,000 --> 02:58:07,000
Back and forth, then of course, when Harry Belafonte and Sidney Poitier and we worked on

2226
02:58:07,000 --> 02:58:14,000
that tour, mostly I was in the office, in literally the office.

2227
02:58:14,000 --> 02:58:17,000
Did you get used to being in the Mississippi when you were there?

2228
02:58:17,000 --> 02:58:22,000
Never. When we left, we went to New Orleans. I said, I'm in Paris.

2229
02:58:22,000 --> 02:58:32,000
And New Orleans was segregated. I feel like I was in Paris. Oh my God.

2230
02:58:32,000 --> 02:58:38,000
No, Judy has all kind of memories about going here and there.

2231
02:58:38,000 --> 02:58:42,000
I didn't go anywhere. I was in that building.

2232
02:58:42,000 --> 02:58:48,000
I thought Bob was going to get killed. I thought I'm going down the road that Rita has gone.

2233
02:58:48,000 --> 02:58:52,000
That's what I thought.

2234
02:58:52,000 --> 02:58:55,000
You were saying about former?

2235
02:58:55,000 --> 02:58:59,000
He didn't have manners.

2236
02:58:59,000 --> 02:59:05,000
When you dealt with him, you didn't do the normal thing about saying something good

2237
02:59:05,000 --> 02:59:08,000
and then you'll say something critical and you'll love it.

2238
02:59:08,000 --> 02:59:10,000
You didn't play those games.

2239
02:59:10,000 --> 02:59:17,000
He didn't play the games either. He'd call you up and he'd say, do blah blah blah.

2240
02:59:17,000 --> 02:59:22,000
I mean, he didn't say, please. He didn't say, he didn't have anything like that.

2241
02:59:22,000 --> 02:59:26,000
But you knew when you knew him that he didn't mean anything by it.

2242
02:59:26,000 --> 02:59:32,000
It wasn't an insult. It was the way he dealt with people.

2243
02:59:32,000 --> 02:59:38,000
I remember when Kennedy was shot. Actually, this is nowhere in any book.

2244
02:59:38,000 --> 02:59:42,000
I picked up the phone. It was him on the phone. It didn't even ring.

2245
02:59:42,000 --> 02:59:49,000
It did not ring. I think I was picking it up to call him. He called me.

2246
02:59:49,000 --> 02:59:55,000
He said, did you hear Kennedy's in shot? He was beyond shocked.

2247
02:59:55,000 --> 02:59:58,000
Of course, who wasn't the judge?

2248
02:59:58,000 --> 03:00:08,000
His first thought was that Oswald had been one of ours in the movement.

2249
03:00:08,000 --> 03:00:13,000
He was very unnerved.

2250
03:00:13,000 --> 03:00:27,000
Then the winter of 64, 65, was when I inadvertently found out that Barney Frank,

2251
03:00:27,000 --> 03:00:36,000
who was then the assistant to Allard K. Lowenstein, had been at a party.

2252
03:00:36,000 --> 03:00:44,000
We were at a party. We heard that Allard K. Lowenstein had been at some meetings.

2253
03:00:44,000 --> 03:00:52,000
I called for him. I said, there's something going on.

2254
03:00:52,000 --> 03:00:56,000
Go meet him. That's the guy. That's what he said.

2255
03:00:56,000 --> 03:01:00,000
Go meet with him.

2256
03:01:00,000 --> 03:01:05,000
I met with him. He told me to write it down immediately.

2257
03:01:05,000 --> 03:01:10,000
I did. Fortunately, Julian found it. He found it. I didn't know where it was.

2258
03:01:10,000 --> 03:01:14,000
I said, what? He found it. I don't know how it's done.

2259
03:01:14,000 --> 03:01:20,000
Of course, this is what they were planning to do. It was planning to get SNCC out of the way.

2260
03:01:20,000 --> 03:01:28,000
It was a meeting of some very high-level people in the civil rights movement in the more acceptable.

2261
03:01:28,000 --> 03:01:32,000
Yes. Yes. Yes.

2262
03:01:32,000 --> 03:01:34,000
Yes. And NAACP. Yes.

2263
03:01:34,000 --> 03:01:39,000
I'm talking about coalition of civil rights groups in New York and the Pacific.

2264
03:01:39,000 --> 03:01:41,000
Yes. That's right.

2265
03:01:41,000 --> 03:01:47,000
And to make sure that the next summer, the summer of 65, which there never was,

2266
03:01:47,000 --> 03:01:51,000
and never occurred, would not be controlled by SNCC.

2267
03:01:51,000 --> 03:01:55,000
That SNCC was too out there, too far out there.

2268
03:01:55,000 --> 03:02:01,000
It didn't like loyalty oath. And he verified it. And I wrote that.

2269
03:02:01,000 --> 03:02:06,000
I mean, what James Forman taught me, of course, James Forman did not teach us to put dates.

2270
03:02:06,000 --> 03:02:08,000
Yes, I noticed that.

2271
03:02:08,000 --> 03:02:12,000
Why is that that? None of us. It's none of us.

2272
03:02:12,000 --> 03:02:15,000
Amy Judy was the only one to put a date on it.

2273
03:02:15,000 --> 03:02:21,000
Well, some letters have dates, but the question is, is that also there is a year?

2274
03:02:21,000 --> 03:02:25,000
That's very common, Sieg. That comes from the newspaper. You read the New York Times.
